/* data+ :: content/domain2.js — lazy-loaded reading module for DAO-002 Domain 2 (Data Acquisition & Preparation). */
window.DATAPLUS = window.DATAPLUS || {}; DATAPLUS.reading = DATAPLUS.reading || {};
DATAPLUS.reading[2] = [];
DATAPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"Data Integration and Acquisition Overview", body:"<p><span class='keyterm'>Data acquisition</span> is the disciplined act of gathering raw data from one or more sources and bringing it into an environment where it can be cleaned, transformed, and analyzed. <span class='keyterm'>Data integration</span> is the closely related practice of combining data from multiple, often heterogeneous, sources into a single unified view. Domain 2 carries the largest preparation workload on the DAO-002 exam because analysts spend a famously large share of their time - frequently cited as 60 to 80 percent - acquiring and preparing data rather than analyzing it. Understanding the full pipeline before drilling into individual techniques keeps every later decision in context.</p><h3>The acquisition-to-analysis pipeline</h3><p>Every data project follows a recognizable arc. First you <em>identify the source</em> - a relational database, a flat file, a REST API, a web scrape, or a survey. Next you <em>extract</em> the data, then <em>profile</em> it to discover its shape and quality problems, then <em>cleanse and transform</em> it into a consistent, analysis-ready form, and finally <em>load</em> it into the target system where reporting happens. The exam expects you to see acquisition and preparation as a single connected workflow rather than isolated tricks, because a poor extraction decision (pulling the wrong grain or the wrong date range) cannot be repaired by later cleansing.</p><ol><li><strong>Identify the source</strong> - a relational database, flat file, REST API, web scrape, or survey.</li><li><strong>Extract</strong> the data from that source.</li><li><strong>Profile</strong> it to discover its shape and quality problems.</li><li><strong>Cleanse and transform</strong> it into a consistent, analysis-ready form.</li><li><strong>Load</strong> it into the target system where reporting happens.</li></ol><h3>Integration methods and patterns</h3><p>Integration can be performed several ways, and the right choice depends on volume, latency tolerance, and how often the data changes. <span class='keyterm'>Batch integration</span> moves large volumes on a schedule (nightly, hourly); <span class='keyterm'>streaming integration</span> moves records continuously in near real time; and <span class='keyterm'>API-based integration</span> pulls data on demand through a defined interface. A frequent integration challenge is <em>schema reconciliation</em> - two sources may both store a customer, but one calls the field cust_id while the other calls it customer_number, and the values may even be typed differently. Resolving these mismatches before combining the data is the heart of integration work.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Method</th><th>Latency</th><th>Typical use</th><th>Tradeoff</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Batch</td><td>Hours/scheduled</td><td>Nightly warehouse loads</td><td>Data is stale between runs</td></tr><tr><td>Streaming</td><td>Seconds/continuous</td><td>Fraud detection, IoT telemetry</td><td>Complex, costly to operate</td></tr><tr><td>API/on-demand</td><td>Per request</td><td>Pulling current exchange rates</td><td>Rate limits, dependency on provider</td></tr><tr><td>Manual import</td><td>Ad hoc</td><td>One-time CSV upload</td><td>Error-prone, not repeatable</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Why a unified view matters</h3><p>The business value of integration is a <em>single, trustworthy picture</em>. When sales data lives in one system and support tickets in another, no one can answer \"do unhappy customers buy less?\" until the two are joined on a common key. Integration is also where data quality problems surface most painfully: duplicate customers, conflicting addresses, and mismatched identifiers all become visible only when sources meet. This is why integration and profiling are taught together - the act of combining sources is itself a discovery process.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>Distinguish <span class='keyterm'>acquisition</span> (getting data in) from <span class='keyterm'>integration</span> (combining sources into one view) from <span class='keyterm'>transformation</span> (reshaping it). A scenario that says \"combine customer records from CRM and billing\" is integration; \"pull yesterday's orders from the API\" is acquisition; \"convert the date strings to a date type\" is transformation.</p></div><h3>Common acquisition pitfalls</h3><p>Several mistakes recur often enough that the exam targets them. Pulling data at the wrong <em>grain</em> (row-per-order when you needed row-per-line-item) forces a costly re-extraction. Ignoring <em>incremental loading</em> and re-pulling an entire table every night wastes time and money when only new rows changed - a <span class='keyterm'>delta load</span> that captures only changes is far more efficient. Failing to record the <em>source and timestamp</em> of acquired data destroys lineage, making it impossible to reproduce or audit a result. Finally, acquiring data without confirming you have the <em>rights</em> to use it - especially scraped web data or third-party feeds - creates governance and legal exposure that a clean technical pipeline cannot offset.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Pitfall</th><th>Consequence</th><th>Remedy</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Wrong grain (row-per-order vs. row-per-line-item)</td><td>Costly re-extraction</td><td>Confirm the required grain before extracting</td></tr><tr><td>Full re-pull every night</td><td>Wasted time and money</td><td>Delta/incremental load of only changed rows</td></tr><tr><td>No source or timestamp recorded</td><td>Lineage destroyed; not reproducible</td><td>Capture source and timestamp at acquisition</td></tr><tr><td>No confirmed rights to use the data</td><td>Governance and legal exposure</td><td>Record license, contract, or consent</td></tr></tbody></table><blockquote>You cannot analyze your way out of a bad acquisition. Get the right data, at the right grain, from a source you can trust and reproduce.</blockquote><h3>Source heterogeneity and the cost of variety</h3><p>The deepest challenge in acquisition is that real sources rarely agree with one another. One system stores dates as text in US format, another as proper date types in ISO format; one represents a missing value as an empty string, another as the literal text \"N/A\", another as the number 999. One source is a transactional relational database optimized for writing single rows quickly; another is a sprawling collection of semi-structured JSON event logs; a third is a vendor API that returns at most a thousand records per request and throttles you if you ask too often. Acquisition is therefore not a single technique but a portfolio of connectors, each with its own authentication, pagination, rate limits, and quirks. Recognizing this <em>variety</em> dimension early lets you budget realistically: a project drawing on five disparate sources will spend most of its effort reconciling them, not analyzing the result. The exam frames many scenarios around exactly this reconciliation work, asking which integration method or which preparation step resolves a stated mismatch.</p><h3>Lineage, reproducibility, and rights</h3><p>A professional acquisition practice records three things about every dataset it pulls: <em>where</em> it came from (the source system, table, or endpoint), <em>when</em> it was captured (a timestamp, because data changes), and <em>by what right</em> it may be used (license, contract, or consent). This metadata is what makes a result <span class='keyterm'>reproducible</span> - able to be regenerated months later when an executive questions a number - and what keeps the organization out of legal trouble. Scraped web data and purchased third-party feeds are especially fraught: a technically flawless pipeline that ingests data the company has no right to use is a governance failure no amount of cleansing can repair. Capturing lineage at the moment of acquisition, rather than trying to reconstruct it afterward, is far cheaper and is the only reliable way to support the audits Domain 5 will demand.</p><h3>Connecting to the rest of Domain 2</h3><p>The sections that follow break the pipeline into its tested skills: querying source systems with joins, unions, filters, and aggregations; optimizing those queries; choosing between ETL and ELT; collecting data through sampling and surveys; profiling data to find missing values, duplicates, outliers, and incompleteness; and finally transforming it through string manipulation, type conversion, scaling, augmentation, and imputation. Each is a tool; this overview is the map that tells you which tool a given scenario calls for. As you read them, keep returning to the three questions this overview raised - what is the source, at what grain and latency, and can the result be reproduced and defended - because nearly every Domain 2 exam item is, at heart, a test of whether you can match a preparation technique to the data problem in front of you.</p>"},
  {heading:"Querying: Joins and the Impact of Each Join", body:"<p>A <span class='keyterm'>join</span> combines rows from two or more tables based on a related column, usually a shared key. Joins are the single most tested SQL skill on the Data+ exam because the <em>type</em> of join you choose directly changes which rows appear in your result - and therefore changes your analysis. Choosing the wrong join silently inflates or shrinks your dataset, producing answers that look plausible but are wrong.</p><h3>The four core join types</h3><p>SQL defines four joins you must know cold. An <span class='keyterm'>INNER JOIN</span> returns only rows that have a match in <em>both</em> tables. A <span class='keyterm'>LEFT JOIN</span> (left outer) returns <em>all</em> rows from the left table plus matching rows from the right, filling unmatched right-side columns with NULL. A <span class='keyterm'>RIGHT JOIN</span> does the mirror image. A <span class='keyterm'>FULL OUTER JOIN</span> returns all rows from both tables, matching where it can and filling NULLs everywhere else. A fifth pattern, the <span class='keyterm'>CROSS JOIN</span>, produces the Cartesian product - every row of one table paired with every row of the other - and is rarely what you want by accident.</p><ul><li><span class='keyterm'>INNER JOIN</span> - returns only rows that have a match in <em>both</em> tables.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>LEFT JOIN</span> (left outer) - all rows from the left table plus matching right rows, NULL-filling unmatched right columns.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>RIGHT JOIN</span> - the mirror image: all right rows plus matching left rows.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>FULL OUTER JOIN</span> - all rows from both tables, matching where possible and NULL-filling elsewhere.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>CROSS JOIN</span> - the Cartesian product of every row paired with every row.</li></ul><pre>SELECT c.customer_name, o.order_total\nFROM customers c\nLEFT JOIN orders o ON c.customer_id = o.customer_id;</pre><p>This LEFT JOIN keeps every customer even if they have never ordered; those customers show a NULL order_total. Swap to INNER JOIN and customers with no orders vanish entirely - a difference that matters enormously if the business question is \"which customers have never purchased?\"</p><h3>How each join changes the row count</h3><table><thead><tr><th>Join type</th><th>Rows returned</th><th>Best for</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>INNER</td><td>Only matched rows in both tables</td><td>\"Customers who placed orders\"</td></tr><tr><td>LEFT</td><td>All left rows + matches</td><td>\"All customers, with orders if any\"</td></tr><tr><td>RIGHT</td><td>All right rows + matches</td><td>\"All orders, with customer if known\"</td></tr><tr><td>FULL OUTER</td><td>All rows from both sides</td><td>Reconciling two lists for gaps on either side</td></tr><tr><td>CROSS</td><td>Every combination (Cartesian)</td><td>Generating all pairings; date scaffolds</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>The hidden danger: join fan-out</h3><p>The most expensive join mistake is <span class='keyterm'>fan-out</span> (also called row multiplication). When you join two tables on a key that is not unique on at least one side - a one-to-many relationship - the rows multiply. If a customer has three orders and each order has two line items, joining customers to orders to line items can turn one customer row into six rows. If you then SUM the order_total, you have double- or triple-counted it. This is the single most common cause of \"my totals are too high\" in real analysis. The defense is to aggregate to the correct grain <em>before</em> joining, or to be deliberate about which side is one and which is many.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>An analyst reports total revenue of 4.2 million, but finance insists it is 1.4 million. The analyst's query joined orders to line_items and summed order_total, multiplying each order's total by its number of line items - a textbook fan-out. The fix is to sum order_total from the orders table directly, or sum line-item amounts instead of the order-level total.</p></div><h3>Self-joins and multi-table joins</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>self-join</span> joins a table to itself, typically to relate rows within the same table - for example matching employees to their managers, where both live in the same employees table. You alias the table twice (e.g. e and m) so the engine can tell the two references apart. Real queries also chain many joins together; the discipline is to know the cardinality of each relationship so you can predict whether a join preserves, expands, or contracts the row set.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>Read the business question for the operative phrase. \"All X, including those without Y\" means a LEFT (outer) join. \"Only X that have Y\" means an INNER join. \"Find X with no matching Y\" means a LEFT JOIN with a <strong>WHERE y.key IS NULL</strong> filter. If totals are suspiciously high after a join, suspect fan-out from a one-to-many relationship.</p></div><h3>Finding the unmatched rows</h3><p>A powerful pattern combines an outer join with a NULL filter to isolate exactly the rows that did not match. The query below returns customers who have never placed an order:</p><pre>SELECT c.customer_name\nFROM customers c\nLEFT JOIN orders o ON c.customer_id = o.customer_id\nWHERE o.customer_id IS NULL;</pre><p>Because the LEFT JOIN fills unmatched right-side columns with NULL, the WHERE clause keeps only those NULL rows - the customers with no order. This anti-join idiom appears constantly in data quality and reconciliation work, and the exam loves to test whether you know that the NULL check, not the join alone, is what isolates the gaps.</p><h3>The ON clause versus the WHERE clause in outer joins</h3><p>A subtlety that trips up even experienced analysts is <em>where</em> a filter belongs when an outer join is involved. A condition placed in the ON clause is applied <em>during</em> the join, before unmatched rows are preserved; a condition placed in WHERE is applied <em>after</em> the join has produced its rows. With an INNER JOIN the distinction rarely matters, but with a LEFT JOIN it changes the answer dramatically. If you write a LEFT JOIN and then add a condition on the right table to the WHERE clause - say WHERE o.status = 'shipped' - you have quietly converted the outer join back into an inner join, because rows where the right side is NULL cannot satisfy a status comparison and get filtered out. To keep all left rows while still restricting the right side, the condition must go in the ON clause instead. This single rule resolves a large class of \"why did my LEFT JOIN lose rows?\" confusion, and the exam occasionally probes it by describing a LEFT JOIN whose results inexplicably exclude unmatched records.</p><h3>Join keys, cardinality, and planning ahead</h3><p>Before writing any join you should know the <span class='keyterm'>cardinality</span> of the relationship - one-to-one, one-to-many, or many-to-many - because cardinality predicts what the join does to your row count. A one-to-one join (a person to their single passport record) preserves the count. A one-to-many join (a customer to their many orders) multiplies the one side by the number of matches, which is the source of fan-out described above. A many-to-many relationship usually requires a <em>bridge</em> or junction table to resolve cleanly, because joining two many sides directly produces an explosive Cartesian-like result.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Cardinality</th><th>Example</th><th>Effect on row count</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>One-to-one</td><td>Person to passport</td><td>Preserves the count</td></tr><tr><td>One-to-many</td><td>Customer to orders</td><td>Multiplies the one side (fan-out)</td></tr><tr><td>Many-to-many</td><td>Students to classes</td><td>Needs a bridge table; explodes if joined directly</td></tr></tbody></table><p> Equally important is that join keys be of the same type and consistently formatted: joining a customer_id stored as an integer in one table to the same id stored as zero-padded text in another will silently match nothing, producing an empty INNER JOIN or all-NULL LEFT JOIN that looks like missing data but is really a type or formatting mismatch. Verifying key types and cardinality first is the habit that prevents most join surprises.</p>"},
  {heading:"Querying: Union, Append, and Concatenate", body:"<p>Where a join combines tables <em>side by side</em> by matching columns, a <span class='keyterm'>union</span> stacks result sets <em>on top of each other</em>, adding rows rather than columns. The Data+ exam treats union, append, and concatenate as a family of vertical-combination operations, and the central skill is knowing how they differ and when each preserves or removes duplicates.</p><h3>UNION versus UNION ALL</h3><p>In SQL, <span class='keyterm'>UNION</span> combines the rows of two queries and <em>removes duplicate rows</em> from the combined result. <span class='keyterm'>UNION ALL</span> combines the rows but <em>keeps every duplicate</em>. The distinction is not cosmetic: UNION must sort and de-duplicate the entire result, which is expensive on large data, whereas UNION ALL simply concatenates and is much faster. Choosing UNION when you actually wanted every record - say, every transaction from two regional tables, including legitimately identical amounts - silently drops valid rows.</p><pre>SELECT customer_id, amount FROM sales_east\nUNION ALL\nSELECT customer_id, amount FROM sales_west;</pre><p>Both queries must have the <em>same number of columns</em>, in the <em>same order</em>, with <em>compatible data types</em>. If sales_east has three columns and sales_west has two, the union fails. This column-alignment rule is the most common union error the exam tests.</p><ul><li><em>Same number of columns</em> in each query.</li><li><em>Same column order</em> across the queries.</li><li><em>Compatible data types</em> position by position.</li></ul><h3>Append in tools and code</h3><p>Outside pure SQL, the same vertical stacking is called an <span class='keyterm'>append</span>. In pandas, pd.concat stacks DataFrames; in Power Query, the \"Append Queries\" command does the same. Appending is the natural way to combine files that share a structure - twelve monthly CSV exports with identical columns become one annual dataset. The key requirement, exactly as in SQL UNION, is structural compatibility: the same columns in a consistent order and type.</p><pre>import pandas as pd\ncombined = pd.concat([jan_df, feb_df, mar_df], ignore_index=True)</pre><h3>Concatenate is two different things</h3><p>The word <span class='keyterm'>concatenate</span> is dangerously overloaded, and the exam exploits the ambiguity. In one sense, concatenate means stacking rows (vertical combination, the same idea as append). In another, far more common sense, concatenate means <em>joining strings together end to end</em> - combining first_name and last_name into a full name, or building an address from parts. SQL uses the || operator or CONCAT() function; Excel uses CONCAT or the &amp; operator; pandas uses the + operator on string columns.</p><pre>SELECT first_name || ' ' || last_name AS full_name FROM employees;\n-- or, portably:\nSELECT CONCAT(first_name, ' ', last_name) AS full_name FROM employees;</pre><table><thead><tr><th>Operation</th><th>Direction</th><th>Duplicates</th><th>Tool example</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>UNION</td><td>Stacks rows</td><td>Removed</td><td>SQL</td></tr><tr><td>UNION ALL</td><td>Stacks rows</td><td>Kept</td><td>SQL</td></tr><tr><td>Append</td><td>Stacks rows</td><td>Kept (unless de-duped)</td><td>pandas concat, Power Query</td></tr><tr><td>Concatenate (string)</td><td>Joins values into one field</td><td>N/A</td><td>CONCAT, ||, &amp;</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>If a question stacks two same-shaped tables and asks which keeps every row including identical ones, the answer is <strong>UNION ALL</strong>; if it must remove duplicates, the answer is <strong>UNION</strong>. If a question combines two text columns into one field, that is <em>string</em> concatenation (CONCAT / || / &amp;), not a union. Watch the word \"concatenate\" carefully - context decides which meaning applies.</p></div><h3>When alignment goes wrong</h3><p>Vertical combination fails or corrupts data in predictable ways. Mismatched column <em>order</em> is insidious because the query may run without error while silently placing phone numbers under the email column. Mismatched <em>types</em> - unioning a text column onto a numeric one - either errors or forces an implicit conversion that mangles values. And combining files where one has an extra column produces ragged results or outright failure. The professional habit is to standardize column names, order, and types <em>before</em> appending, and to validate the row count of the result against the sum of the inputs.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>An analyst appends twelve monthly sales files and expects 120,000 rows but gets 96,000. UNION (not UNION ALL) silently removed 24,000 rows that happened to be identical - same product, same amount, same day. Because real repeat sales are legitimate, the correct operation was UNION ALL, and the de-duplicated result understated revenue.</p></div><h3>Set operations beyond UNION</h3><p>UNION belongs to a family of <em>set operators</em> that the exam may reference. <span class='keyterm'>INTERSECT</span> returns only the rows that appear in <em>both</em> result sets - useful for answering \"which customers appear in both the email list and the purchase list?\" <span class='keyterm'>EXCEPT</span> (called MINUS in Oracle) returns rows in the first result set that are <em>not</em> in the second - \"which subscribers have never purchased?\" Like UNION, these operators require the two queries to have matching column counts and compatible types, and like UNION they remove duplicates by default. They are a concise alternative to the LEFT JOIN...IS NULL anti-join pattern for comparing two lists, and recognizing that INTERSECT means \"in both\" while EXCEPT means \"in the first only\" is occasionally tested directly.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Set operator</th><th>Returns</th><th>Plain-English question</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>UNION</td><td>Rows in either set, duplicates removed</td><td>\"Everyone in either list\"</td></tr><tr><td>INTERSECT</td><td>Rows in both sets</td><td>\"Who is in both lists?\"</td></tr><tr><td>EXCEPT (MINUS)</td><td>Rows in the first set only</td><td>\"Who is in the first list but not the second?\"</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Performance and validation of vertical combination</h3><p>Because UNION must sort the combined result to find and remove duplicates, it is measurably slower than UNION ALL on large datasets, and it consumes temporary space to do the sort. The professional default is therefore to use UNION ALL whenever you know the inputs cannot contain unwanted duplicates - for instance when appending non-overlapping monthly partitions - and to reserve UNION for the genuine case where de-duplication is required. After any append, validate the outcome with a simple arithmetic check: the row count of the combined result should equal the sum of the input row counts when using UNION ALL, and should be less than or equal to that sum when using UNION. A combined count that is unexpectedly low after UNION ALL points to a filter or type-coercion problem; a count that exactly matches the sum after a plain UNION means there were no duplicates at all, which may itself be worth questioning.</p><h3>Combining the patterns</h3><p>Real pipelines mix these operations: you might UNION ALL twelve monthly files into one table, then JOIN that table to a product dimension to add descriptions, then GROUP BY to summarize. Recognizing that union adds rows while join adds columns is the conceptual anchor that keeps these steps straight, and it is a distinction the exam returns to repeatedly because so many learners conflate the two. The mental test is direction: if a question gives you two tables with the <em>same</em> columns and asks you to combine them, that is vertical (union/append); if it gives you two tables with <em>different</em> columns linked by a shared key, that is horizontal (join/merge).</p>"},
  {heading:"Querying: Filtering, Grouping, and Aggregation", body:"<p>Three SQL clauses do the heavy lifting of summarizing data: <span class='keyterm'>WHERE</span> filters rows, <span class='keyterm'>GROUP BY</span> collapses rows into groups, and aggregate functions compute one value per group. Add <span class='keyterm'>HAVING</span> to filter the groups themselves, and you have the toolkit behind nearly every business report. The exam tests not just syntax but the precise <em>order</em> in which these operations apply, because that order determines what each clause can reference.</p><h3>Filtering rows with WHERE</h3><p>The WHERE clause restricts which rows enter the result, evaluated <em>before</em> any grouping. It supports comparison operators (=, &lt;, &gt;, &lt;&gt;), logical operators (AND, OR, NOT), ranges (BETWEEN), set membership (IN), pattern matching (LIKE), and NULL tests (IS NULL / IS NOT NULL). A subtle but heavily tested rule: NULL cannot be compared with = or &lt;&gt;; you must use IS NULL, because NULL means \"unknown\" and any comparison with unknown yields unknown, not true.</p><pre>SELECT * FROM orders\nWHERE order_date BETWEEN '2025-01-01' AND '2025-03-31'\n  AND status IN ('shipped','delivered')\n  AND tracking_number IS NOT NULL;</pre><h3>Aggregating with GROUP BY</h3><p>Aggregate functions reduce many rows to one summary value: <span class='keyterm'>COUNT</span>, <span class='keyterm'>SUM</span>, <span class='keyterm'>AVG</span>, <span class='keyterm'>MIN</span>, and <span class='keyterm'>MAX</span>. Used alone they collapse the whole table to a single row. Add GROUP BY and they compute one value <em>per group</em>. The iron rule of GROUP BY: every column in the SELECT list must either appear in the GROUP BY clause or be wrapped in an aggregate function. Violating this rule is one of the most common SQL errors and a favorite exam trap.</p><pre>SELECT region, COUNT(*) AS order_count, SUM(order_total) AS revenue\nFROM orders\nWHERE order_date >= '2025-01-01'\nGROUP BY region\nHAVING SUM(order_total) > 100000\nORDER BY revenue DESC;</pre><h3>WHERE versus HAVING</h3><p>This distinction is the single most tested idea in the section. <span class='keyterm'>WHERE</span> filters <em>individual rows before</em> grouping; <span class='keyterm'>HAVING</span> filters <em>groups after</em> aggregation. You cannot put an aggregate in WHERE (WHERE SUM(...) &gt; 100000 is illegal) because aggregates do not exist until grouping happens. Conversely, filtering on a non-aggregated column belongs in WHERE for efficiency, since it shrinks the data before the expensive grouping step.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Clause</th><th>Filters</th><th>When</th><th>Can use aggregates?</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>WHERE</td><td>Rows</td><td>Before grouping</td><td>No</td></tr><tr><td>GROUP BY</td><td>(collapses rows)</td><td>After WHERE</td><td>Defines the groups</td></tr><tr><td>HAVING</td><td>Groups</td><td>After aggregation</td><td>Yes</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>The logical order of execution</h3><p>SQL is written in one order but executed in another, and knowing the execution order resolves most confusion. The engine processes FROM and JOINs first, then WHERE, then GROUP BY, then HAVING, then SELECT (including column aliases), then ORDER BY, and finally LIMIT/TOP. This is why you cannot reference a SELECT alias in WHERE - the alias does not exist yet when WHERE runs - but you often can in ORDER BY, which runs after SELECT.</p><ol><li><strong>FROM / JOIN</strong> - assemble the source rows.</li><li><strong>WHERE</strong> - filter individual rows.</li><li><strong>GROUP BY</strong> - collapse rows into groups.</li><li><strong>HAVING</strong> - filter the groups.</li><li><strong>SELECT</strong> - project columns and compute aliases.</li><li><strong>ORDER BY</strong> - sort the result (can use aliases).</li><li><strong>LIMIT / TOP</strong> - cap the number of rows returned.</li></ol><blockquote>FROM, WHERE, GROUP BY, HAVING, SELECT, ORDER BY, LIMIT. Filter rows early, filter groups late.</blockquote><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>If a question filters on a raw column value (status = 'shipped'), use <strong>WHERE</strong>. If it filters on an aggregate result (\"groups whose total exceeds 100,000\" or \"customers with more than 5 orders\"), use <strong>HAVING</strong>. Remember COUNT(*) counts all rows including NULLs, while COUNT(column) counts only non-NULL values in that column - a distinction that changes the answer.</p></div><h3>COUNT subtleties and NULL handling</h3><p>Aggregates treat NULL in a specific way the exam probes. COUNT(*) counts every row; COUNT(column) counts only rows where that column is not NULL; COUNT(DISTINCT column) counts unique non-NULL values. Likewise SUM and AVG <em>ignore</em> NULLs entirely rather than treating them as zero - which means AVG(salary) over rows with some NULL salaries divides by the count of non-NULL salaries, not the total row count. Misreading this leads to averages that are too high.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Expression</th><th>Counts</th><th>NULL handling</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>COUNT(*)</td><td>Every row</td><td>Includes rows with NULLs</td></tr><tr><td>COUNT(column)</td><td>Rows where the column is not NULL</td><td>Ignores NULLs</td></tr><tr><td>COUNT(DISTINCT column)</td><td>Unique non-NULL values</td><td>Ignores NULLs and duplicates</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>A manager asks for the average order value per region, but only for regions with more than 1,000 orders. The analyst filters dates in WHERE, groups by region, computes AVG(order_total), and applies HAVING COUNT(*) &gt; 1000 to keep only the high-volume regions. Putting the count test in WHERE would have failed, because the count does not exist until the groups are formed.</p></div><h3>Grouping by multiple columns and the grain of a summary</h3><p>GROUP BY accepts more than one column, and the combination defines the <span class='keyterm'>grain</span> of the summary - the level of detail each result row represents. GROUP BY region produces one row per region; GROUP BY region, product_category produces one row per region-and-category combination, a finer grain. Understanding grain is essential because it controls what your aggregates mean: SUM(order_total) grouped by region is regional revenue, but the same sum grouped by region and month is monthly regional revenue. A frequent error is grouping at the wrong grain and then misreading the totals - for example grouping by both customer and order when you wanted a per-customer summary, which leaves the data essentially un-summarized. When a report's numbers seem too granular or too coarse, the GROUP BY column list is the first place to look.</p><h3>DISTINCT versus GROUP BY</h3><p>Both DISTINCT and GROUP BY can remove duplicate values, which leads to confusion about when to use each. SELECT DISTINCT region simply returns the unique list of regions with no aggregation; GROUP BY region does the same de-duplication but additionally lets you attach aggregate functions to each group. The rule of thumb is to use DISTINCT when you only need the unique values and GROUP BY when you need a computed measure alongside them. Overusing DISTINCT to paper over a fan-out problem is a classic anti-pattern: if a join multiplied your rows, SELECT DISTINCT may hide the duplicates visually while your SUM and COUNT remain inflated, because those aggregates ran on the multiplied rows before DISTINCT was applied. The correct fix is to remove the fan-out at its source, not to mask it with DISTINCT.</p>"},
  {heading:"Basic Query Optimization", body:"<p>A query that returns the right answer is not finished if it takes an hour to run or locks a production table. <span class='keyterm'>Query optimization</span> is the set of techniques that make queries faster and cheaper without changing their results. The Data+ exam focuses on the practical levers an analyst controls: indexing, parameterization, working with subsets, temporary tables, and the careful use of nested queries.</p><ul><li><span class='keyterm'>Indexing</span> - speed reads that filter, join, or sort on a column.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Limiting to subsets</span> - fewer columns (no SELECT *) and fewer rows (WHERE + LIMIT).</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Parameterization</span> - reuse execution plans and block SQL injection.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Temporary tables and CTEs</span> - compute an expensive intermediate result once.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Nested queries</span> - used carefully, since correlated subqueries can be slow.</li></ul><h3>Indexing</h3><p>An <span class='keyterm'>index</span> is a separate data structure - usually a B-tree - that lets the database find rows by a key value without scanning the entire table, much like the index at the back of a book. An index on customer_id turns a full-table scan into a fast lookup. Indexes dramatically speed up <em>reads</em> that filter or join on the indexed column, but they impose a cost on <em>writes</em>, because every INSERT, UPDATE, or DELETE must also update the index. This is the central tradeoff: index the columns you frequently filter, join, or sort on, but do not index everything, because over-indexing slows down data loading.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Index helps when you</th><th>Index hurts when you</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Filter in WHERE on the column</td><td>Insert/update/delete heavily</td></tr><tr><td>JOIN on the column</td><td>Index columns rarely queried</td></tr><tr><td>ORDER BY the column</td><td>Index very low-cardinality columns (e.g. a boolean)</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Limiting to subsets</h3><p>The cheapest optimization is asking for less data. Use <span class='keyterm'>LIMIT</span> (or TOP in SQL Server) to cap rows while developing a query, select only the columns you need instead of SELECT *, and push filters into WHERE so the database discards unwanted rows early. Pulling a 10-million-row table into a notebook only to filter it in pandas wastes network, memory, and time; filtering at the source is almost always faster.</p><pre>-- Slow: pull everything, filter later\nSELECT * FROM transactions;\n-- Fast: filter and project at the source\nSELECT txn_id, amount, txn_date\nFROM transactions\nWHERE txn_date >= '2025-01-01'\nLIMIT 1000;</pre><h3>Parameterization</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Parameterized queries</span> use placeholders for values rather than embedding literals directly in the SQL string. The database can then <em>reuse the compiled execution plan</em> across many executions with different values, avoiding repeated parsing and planning. Parameterization also delivers a critical security benefit: it prevents <span class='keyterm'>SQL injection</span>, because user input is treated strictly as data, never as executable SQL. This dual benefit - performance plus security - is exactly why the exam emphasizes it.</p><pre>-- Parameterized (Python DB-API style)\ncur.execute(\"SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = %s\", (user_email,))</pre><h3>Temporary tables and CTEs</h3><p>When a query grows complex, breaking it into stages improves both readability and speed. A <span class='keyterm'>temporary table</span> stores an intermediate result that you reference multiple times, so the database computes it once instead of repeatedly. A <span class='keyterm'>common table expression</span> (CTE), written with the WITH keyword, names a subquery so the main query reads cleanly. Materializing an expensive intermediate result into a temp table is a common way to rescue a slow report that recomputes the same aggregate over and over.</p><pre>WITH regional_totals AS (\n  SELECT region, SUM(order_total) AS revenue\n  FROM orders\n  GROUP BY region\n)\nSELECT region, revenue\nFROM regional_totals\nWHERE revenue > 100000;</pre><h3>Nested queries (subqueries)</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>subquery</span> (nested query) is a query inside another query. Subqueries are powerful but can be slow, especially <em>correlated</em> subqueries that re-run once per outer row. Often a join or a CTE expresses the same logic more efficiently. The exam expects you to recognize that a deeply nested or correlated subquery is a common performance culprit and that rewriting it as a join frequently helps.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>If a query that filters or joins on a column is slow on a large table, the first remedy is usually an <strong>index</strong> on that column. If the same query runs thousands of times with different values, <strong>parameterization</strong> lets the plan be reused and blocks SQL injection. To speed an oversized pull, <strong>limit the subset</strong> - fewer columns (no SELECT *), fewer rows (WHERE + LIMIT) - before doing anything else.</p></div><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>A dashboard query joining a 50-million-row events table to a users table on user_id takes four minutes. Adding an index on events.user_id reduces the join from a full scan to indexed lookups, cutting the run to seconds. The analyst also replaces SELECT * with the five columns the dashboard actually uses, further shrinking the data moved across the network.</p></div><h3>Reading the execution plan</h3><p>The single most useful optimization skill is reading a query's <span class='keyterm'>execution plan</span> - the step-by-step strategy the database chose to satisfy your query, viewable with EXPLAIN (or EXPLAIN ANALYZE for actual timings). The plan reveals whether the engine performed a full <em>table scan</em> (reading every row, slow) or an <em>index seek</em> (jumping straight to matching rows, fast), the order in which tables were joined, and where the bulk of the time and rows were spent. When a query is slow, the plan usually points straight at the culprit: a sequential scan on a large table where you expected an index seek tells you an index is missing or is being bypassed because a function was applied to the indexed column. Optimizing without reading the plan is guesswork; reading it turns optimization into diagnosis.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Access method</th><th>How it reads</th><th>Speed</th><th>Signals</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Table scan (sequential scan)</td><td>Reads every row in the table</td><td>Slow on large tables</td><td>Missing index, or a function applied to the indexed column</td></tr><tr><td>Index seek</td><td>Jumps straight to matching rows</td><td>Fast</td><td>A usable index exists and the column is left \"bare\"</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Why functions on columns defeat indexes</h3><p>A common and tested pitfall is that wrapping an indexed column in a function prevents the index from being used. WHERE YEAR(order_date) = 2025 cannot use an index on order_date, because the database must compute YEAR() for every row before it can compare - forcing a full scan. Rewriting the same logic as a range, WHERE order_date &gt;= '2025-01-01' AND order_date &lt; '2026-01-01', lets the engine use the index directly. The same trap applies to UPPER() on a name column or arithmetic on a numeric key. The principle is to keep the indexed column \"bare\" on one side of the comparison and move any transformation to the constant side. This rule, combined with proper indexing, resolves a surprising share of real-world slow queries.</p><h3>A reasoned approach</h3><p>Optimization should be evidence-driven, not superstitious. Examine the query's execution plan to see where time is spent, target the most expensive operation first, and re-measure after each change. Indexing a column no query filters on, or breaking a fast query into temp tables it does not need, adds complexity without benefit. The goal is the smallest change that delivers the largest, verified speedup - and the discipline of measuring before and after every change is what keeps optimization honest rather than cargo-cult.</p>"},
  {heading:"ETL vs ELT", body:"<p>Moving data from sources into an analytic store follows one of two architectural patterns: <span class='keyterm'>ETL</span> (Extract, Transform, Load) or <span class='keyterm'>ELT</span> (Extract, Load, Transform). They use the same three operations but in a different order, and that reordering has large consequences for where the work happens, how flexible the pipeline is, and which tools you reach for. The exam reliably tests the difference and when each is appropriate.</p><h3>The three operations</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Extract</span> pulls raw data from sources - databases, APIs, files, logs. <span class='keyterm'>Transform</span> cleans, reshapes, standardizes, and enriches the data: deduplicating, converting types, joining lookups, applying business rules. <span class='keyterm'>Load</span> writes the data into the target system, typically a data warehouse or data lake. Every pipeline does all three; the only question is whether transformation happens <em>before</em> or <em>after</em> loading.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Operation</th><th>What it does</th><th>Examples</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Extract</td><td>Pulls raw data from sources</td><td>Databases, APIs, files, logs</td></tr><tr><td>Transform</td><td>Cleans, reshapes, standardizes, enriches</td><td>Dedup, type conversion, lookups, business rules</td></tr><tr><td>Load</td><td>Writes data into the target</td><td>Data warehouse or data lake</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>ETL: transform before loading</h3><p>In the classic <span class='keyterm'>ETL</span> pattern, data is extracted, transformed in a separate processing engine (or staging server), and only the cleaned, conformed result is loaded into the warehouse. ETL suits traditional, on-premise data warehouses with structured data and well-defined schemas. Because only refined data lands in the warehouse, storage is used efficiently and the loaded data is immediately analysis-ready. The cost is rigidity: transformations are defined up front, so a new question requiring raw detail may force you to rebuild the pipeline.</p><h3>ELT: load first, transform in place</h3><p>In <span class='keyterm'>ELT</span>, raw data is extracted and loaded immediately into a powerful target - typically a cloud data warehouse like Snowflake, BigQuery, or Redshift, or a data lake - and transformation happens <em>inside</em> that system using its compute. ELT exploits the near-infinite, elastic compute and cheap storage of modern cloud platforms. Because the raw data is preserved, analysts can re-transform it for new questions without re-extracting. ELT shines with large volumes, semi-structured data (JSON), and schema-on-read workflows.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Aspect</th><th>ETL</th><th>ELT</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Transform location</td><td>Separate engine, before load</td><td>Inside target, after load</td></tr><tr><td>Best for</td><td>On-prem warehouses, structured data</td><td>Cloud warehouses/lakes, big & semi-structured data</td></tr><tr><td>Raw data retained?</td><td>No (only refined data lands)</td><td>Yes (raw preserved for reuse)</td></tr><tr><td>Flexibility</td><td>Lower - transforms fixed up front</td><td>Higher - re-transform on demand</td></tr><tr><td>Storage of raw</td><td>Minimized</td><td>Larger (raw + transformed)</td></tr><tr><td>Compliance edge</td><td>Sensitive data scrubbed before landing</td><td>Raw (possibly sensitive) lands first</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>The only difference is the order of the last two letters. <strong>ETL</strong> transforms <em>before</em> loading (refined data lands, classic on-prem warehouse). <strong>ELT</strong> loads raw <em>first</em> and transforms inside a powerful cloud target (flexible, big-data and semi-structured friendly). If a scenario stresses cloud scale, raw-data retention, or schema-on-read, lean ELT; if it stresses on-prem, fixed schemas, or scrubbing sensitive data before it lands, lean ETL.</p></div><h3>The compliance and security angle</h3><p>The ordering has a privacy dimension the exam sometimes raises. In ETL, you can mask, tokenize, or drop sensitive fields <em>during transformation</em>, so the warehouse never stores raw PII - a real advantage under regulations like GDPR. In ELT, raw data (potentially including sensitive fields) lands first, so the target system itself must be secured and access-controlled, and de-identification happens inside it. Neither is inherently safer; they shift <em>where</em> the protection must be applied.</p><h3>Staging, orchestration, and idempotency</h3><p>Both patterns rely on supporting concepts. A <span class='keyterm'>staging area</span> holds raw extracted data temporarily before transformation. <span class='keyterm'>Orchestration</span> tools (Airflow, dbt, SSIS, Azure Data Factory) schedule and sequence the steps and handle failures. A well-designed pipeline is <span class='keyterm'>idempotent</span> - re-running it produces the same result rather than duplicating data - which matters when a nightly job fails midway and must be safely retried.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>A startup moves to Snowflake and wants analysts to explore raw event logs and re-shape them for new questions without waiting on the data team. ELT fits: load the raw JSON events directly into Snowflake, then write SQL transformations inside the warehouse. A bank with strict rules that PII must never be stored unmasked chooses ETL instead, scrubbing sensitive fields before the data ever lands in the warehouse.</p></div><h3>The full transformation workload both patterns share</h3><p>Whether transformation happens before or after loading, the <em>work</em> it performs is the same and is worth enumerating because it ties together the entire preparation half of Domain 2. Transformation includes cleansing (removing duplicates, fixing invalid values, handling missing data), conforming (standardizing types, formats, units, and category labels into a common vocabulary), enriching (joining reference data, computing derived fields), aggregating (rolling detail up to a reporting grain), and structuring (reshaping nested or wide data into the model the target expects).</p><ul><li><strong>Cleansing</strong> - removing duplicates, fixing invalid values, handling missing data.</li><li><strong>Conforming</strong> - standardizing types, formats, units, and category labels into a common vocabulary.</li><li><strong>Enriching</strong> - joining reference data and computing derived fields.</li><li><strong>Aggregating</strong> - rolling detail up to a reporting grain.</li><li><strong>Structuring</strong> - reshaping nested or wide data into the model the target expects.</li></ul><p>In ETL these steps run in a dedicated engine on a staging server; in ELT they run as SQL or stored procedures inside the warehouse. The exam may describe one of these activities and ask where it occurs in each pattern - the answer is always \"in the transform step,\" but the <em>location</em> of that step (separate engine vs. inside the target) is what distinguishes ETL from ELT.</p><h3>Incremental loading and change data capture</h3><p>Neither pattern is efficient if it re-processes everything on every run. Mature pipelines use <span class='keyterm'>incremental loading</span>, moving only the data that changed since the last run, and <span class='keyterm'>change data capture</span> (CDC), which detects inserts, updates, and deletes at the source - often by reading the database transaction log - so downstream systems can apply just those deltas. Incremental strategies depend on a reliable marker: a last-modified timestamp, an auto-incrementing id, or a CDC feed. Getting incremental loading right is where much real ETL/ELT engineering effort goes, because a naive \"truncate and reload\" works fine on a small table but becomes impossibly slow and expensive as data grows into the hundreds of millions of rows.</p><h3>Choosing in practice</h3><p>The decision hinges on volume, data variety, infrastructure, and governance. Massive, varied, fast-growing data on a cloud platform favors ELT; modest, structured, sensitive data on fixed on-prem infrastructure favors ETL. Many modern shops blend both, using ELT for bulk loading and lightweight in-warehouse transforms while still scrubbing the most sensitive fields before landing them. The right answer on the exam follows the scenario's emphasis: cloud scale and flexibility point to ELT, while fixed schemas and pre-load sensitive-data scrubbing point to ETL.</p>"},
  {heading:"Data Collection: Sampling and Surveying", body:"<p>Not all data arrives from existing systems; much of it must be <em>collected</em>. Two collection disciplines dominate: <span class='keyterm'>sampling</span>, the art of selecting a representative subset of a larger population, and <span class='keyterm'>surveying</span>, the design of instruments that gather data directly from people. Both introduce error if done carelessly, and the exam tests whether you can recognize sound versus biased collection.</p><h3>Why we sample</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>population</span> is the entire set you care about; a <span class='keyterm'>sample</span> is the subset you actually examine. We sample because studying an entire population is often impossible, too expensive, or too slow. The goal is a sample that is <em>representative</em> - one whose characteristics mirror the population - so that conclusions drawn from the sample generalize. The enemy of representativeness is <span class='keyterm'>sampling bias</span>, a systematic skew that makes the sample unlike the population.</p><h3>Sampling methods</h3><table><thead><tr><th>Method</th><th>How it works</th><th>Strength / risk</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Simple random</td><td>Every member has equal selection chance</td><td>Unbiased; needs a full population list</td></tr><tr><td>Systematic</td><td>Pick every nth member</td><td>Easy; risky if list has a hidden cycle</td></tr><tr><td>Stratified</td><td>Divide into subgroups, sample each proportionally</td><td>Ensures subgroup representation</td></tr><tr><td>Cluster</td><td>Randomly pick whole groups (e.g. stores), sample all within</td><td>Cheap logistics; less precise</td></tr><tr><td>Convenience</td><td>Whoever is easiest to reach</td><td>Fast but highly biased</td></tr></tbody></table><p><span class='keyterm'>Stratified sampling</span> deserves special attention because it directly fights bias: by dividing the population into strata (say, age brackets or regions) and sampling each in proportion to its size, you guarantee that small but important subgroups are not crowded out by chance. <span class='keyterm'>Convenience sampling</span>, by contrast, is the classic cautionary tale - surveying only mall shoppers or only website visitors who opt in produces a sample that systematically excludes anyone unlike them.</p><h3>Sample size and its tradeoffs</h3><p>Larger samples reduce random sampling error and narrow confidence intervals, but with diminishing returns and rising cost. Crucially, a large sample does <em>not</em> fix bias: a million responses from a self-selected online poll are still unrepresentative of the general public. Size addresses precision; method addresses bias. Mistaking one for the other is a frequent error the exam targets.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p><strong>Stratified</strong> sampling ensures every subgroup is represented proportionally; <strong>cluster</strong> sampling picks whole groups to save cost; <strong>convenience</strong> sampling is fast but biased. Remember: increasing sample <em>size</em> reduces random error but never removes <em>bias</em> from a flawed selection method.</p></div><h3>Survey design</h3><p>Surveys collect self-reported data and are only as good as their questions. Several design flaws recur. A <span class='keyterm'>leading question</span> nudges respondents toward an answer (\"How much did you enjoy our excellent service?\"). A <span class='keyterm'>double-barreled question</span> asks two things at once (\"Was the staff friendly and fast?\"), making answers ambiguous. <span class='keyterm'>Response bias</span> arises when respondents answer untruthfully - to look good (social desirability) or to please the surveyor. <span class='keyterm'>Non-response bias</span> occurs when those who decline differ systematically from those who answer, skewing results even with a good initial sample.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Survey flaw</th><th>What goes wrong</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Leading question</td><td>Wording pushes a particular answer</td></tr><tr><td>Double-barreled</td><td>Two questions in one; answer is ambiguous</td></tr><tr><td>Response bias</td><td>People answer untruthfully or to please</td></tr><tr><td>Non-response bias</td><td>Those who skip differ from those who answer</td></tr><tr><td>Sampling bias</td><td>The respondent pool is not representative</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Open versus closed questions</h3><p>Survey items are <span class='keyterm'>closed-ended</span> (fixed choices, Likert scales, yes/no) or <span class='keyterm'>open-ended</span> (free text). Closed questions are easy to aggregate and quantify but constrain answers to the options offered; open questions capture nuance but require text analysis to summarize. Good instruments mix both, using closed questions for the metrics and a few open questions to surface the unexpected.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>A company emails a satisfaction survey and only delighted and furious customers bother to respond, while the indifferent majority ignores it. The resulting bimodal scores misrepresent the typical customer - a textbook case of non-response bias. Following up with a stratified random sample of all customers, including reminders, produces a far more representative picture.</p></div><h3>Probability versus non-probability sampling</h3><p>A useful organizing distinction is between <span class='keyterm'>probability sampling</span>, where every population member has a known, non-zero chance of selection (simple random, systematic, stratified, and cluster all qualify), and <span class='keyterm'>non-probability sampling</span>, where selection is not random (convenience, quota, and snowball sampling). Only probability sampling supports valid statistical inference - the calculation of margins of error and confidence intervals that lets you generalize from sample to population with a quantified uncertainty. Non-probability methods are faster and cheaper and are fine for exploratory or qualitative work, but you cannot legitimately attach a margin of error to a convenience sample, and claims that do so are statistically unsound. The exam expects you to know that the ability to generalize rigorously depends on a probability-based selection method, not merely on a large number of responses.</p><h3>Sources of survey error beyond the questions</h3><p>Survey quality is threatened at several stages, and naming each helps you diagnose a flawed instrument. <span class='keyterm'>Coverage error</span> arises when the list you sample from (the sampling frame) omits part of the target population - a phone survey misses people without phones. <span class='keyterm'>Sampling error</span> is the natural random variation between a sample and the population, shrinking as sample size grows. <span class='keyterm'>Measurement error</span> comes from poorly worded questions, confusing scales, or interviewer influence. And <span class='keyterm'>processing error</span> creeps in during data entry and coding of responses. Distinguishing these matters because the remedies differ: coverage error needs a better frame, sampling error needs a larger sample, measurement error needs better question design, and processing error needs validation and double-entry checks. A survey can be undone by any one of them, so a rigorous design addresses all four.</p><ul><li><span class='keyterm'>Coverage error</span> - the sampling frame omits part of the target population; fix with a better frame.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Sampling error</span> - natural random variation between sample and population; fix with a larger sample.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Measurement error</span> - poorly worded questions or interviewer influence; fix with better question design.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Processing error</span> - mistakes during data entry and coding; fix with validation and double-entry checks.</li></ul><h3>Collection and downstream quality</h3><p>Collection choices echo through the entire pipeline. A biased sample cannot be cleansed into representativeness, and ambiguous survey wording cannot be re-coded into clarity after the fact. This is why the exam frames sampling and surveying as part of data <em>acquisition</em>: the quality ceiling of any analysis is set the moment the data is collected, and no amount of later transformation can raise it. When a scenario describes a disappointing or misleading result that traces back to who was asked or how the question was phrased, the root cause - and the correct answer - lies in the collection design, not in the analysis that followed.</p>"},
  {heading:"Exploring Missing Values and Null Causes", body:"<p>Real data is rarely complete. <span class='keyterm'>Missing values</span> - empty cells, NULLs, blanks, placeholder codes - are among the first and most consequential problems an analyst confronts during <span class='keyterm'>data profiling</span>. The exam expects you to recognize how missingness arises, how databases represent it, and why the <em>reason</em> a value is missing changes how you should handle it.</p><h3>What NULL really means</h3><p>In a database, <span class='keyterm'>NULL</span> represents the <em>absence</em> of a value - it means \"unknown\" or \"not applicable,\" not zero and not an empty string. This distinction is critical and heavily tested. Zero is a known quantity (the account balance is 0); an empty string is a known, deliberately empty text; NULL is the absence of any known value. Because NULL means \"unknown,\" comparisons behave under <em>three-valued logic</em>: anything compared to NULL yields NULL (unknown), not true or false. That is why WHERE balance = NULL never matches anything; you must write WHERE balance IS NULL.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Representation</th><th>Meaning</th><th>Example</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>NULL</td><td>Unknown / not applicable</td><td>Missing phone number</td></tr><tr><td>0</td><td>A known numeric zero</td><td>Zero items in cart</td></tr><tr><td>'' (empty string)</td><td>A known empty text</td><td>Blank middle name field</td></tr><tr><td>Placeholder (e.g. -1, 9999, 'N/A')</td><td>Disguised missing value</td><td>Age recorded as 999</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Causes of missing data</h3><p>Missingness has many origins, and naming the cause guides the fix. Data may be missing because a field was <em>optional</em> and the user skipped it, because of a <em>data entry error</em> or skipped step, because of a <em>system or integration failure</em> that dropped values during transfer, because the value is genuinely <em>not applicable</em> (a spouse's name for a single person), or because of <em>privacy redaction</em>. A particularly dangerous cause is the <em>disguised missing value</em> - a placeholder like 999 for age or -1 for price - which masquerades as real data and silently corrupts averages and sums until profiling reveals it.</p><ul><li><em>Optional field skipped</em> - the user left it blank.</li><li><em>Data entry error or skipped step</em> during capture.</li><li><em>System or integration failure</em> that dropped values during transfer.</li><li><em>Genuinely not applicable</em> - a spouse's name for a single person.</li><li><em>Privacy redaction</em> - the value was deliberately withheld.</li><li><em>Disguised missing value</em> - a placeholder like 999 or -1 posing as real data.</li></ul><h3>The three missingness mechanisms</h3><p>Statisticians classify <em>why</em> data is missing into three mechanisms, and the exam touches on the concept because it dictates whether your handling will bias results. <span class='keyterm'>MCAR</span> (Missing Completely At Random) means the missingness is unrelated to anything - a sensor randomly drops readings. <span class='keyterm'>MAR</span> (Missing At Random) means missingness depends on other observed variables - older respondents skip a tech question. <span class='keyterm'>MNAR</span> (Missing Not At Random) means missingness depends on the missing value itself - high earners decline to report income. MNAR is the most dangerous because simply dropping or mean-filling those rows systematically biases the result.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Mechanism</th><th>Missingness depends on</th><th>Example</th><th>Risk</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>MCAR</td><td>Nothing - purely random</td><td>Sensor randomly drops readings</td><td>Low; deletion is usually safe</td></tr><tr><td>MAR</td><td>Other observed variables</td><td>Older respondents skip a tech question</td><td>Moderate; model-based imputation works</td></tr><tr><td>MNAR</td><td>The missing value itself</td><td>High earners decline to report income</td><td>High; deletion and mean-fill both bias</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p><span class='keyterm'>NULL</span> is not zero and not an empty string - it is the absence of a value, and comparisons to it must use <strong>IS NULL</strong> / <strong>IS NOT NULL</strong>. Beware <em>disguised</em> missing values (999, -1, 'N/A') that profiling must catch, because they corrupt aggregates while looking like real data. The <em>reason</em> data is missing (MCAR/MAR/MNAR) determines whether deletion or imputation is safe.</p></div><h3>Detecting missing values</h3><p>Profiling for missingness combines counting and visualizing. In SQL you count NULLs per column; in pandas you use isnull().sum(). You also hunt for disguised missing values by examining distributions for suspicious spikes - a cluster of ages at exactly 999, or prices of -1 - that betray placeholder codes.</p><pre>-- Count missing per column in SQL\nSELECT\n  COUNT(*) AS total_rows,\n  COUNT(*) - COUNT(phone) AS missing_phone,\n  COUNT(*) - COUNT(email) AS missing_email\nFROM customers;</pre><pre># pandas: missing count and percentage per column\ndf.isnull().sum()\n(df.isnull().mean() * 100).round(1)  # percent missing</pre><h3>Why the cause matters before the fix</h3><p>Profiling missingness is not just bookkeeping; it shapes strategy. If 2 percent of phone numbers are MCAR, dropping those rows is usually safe. If 40 percent of income values are MNAR because high earners refuse to disclose, neither deletion nor mean imputation is acceptable - both understate true income. The handling techniques (deletion, imputation) are covered later in Domain 2; the point of <em>this</em> exploration step is to quantify the missingness and diagnose its cause so the right technique is chosen.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>An analyst computes average customer age as 612 and is baffled. Profiling reveals thousands of records with age 9999, a placeholder the source system used for \"unknown.\" Because these were treated as real numbers, they inflated the average. Replacing 9999 with proper NULLs - so aggregates ignore them - immediately restores a sensible average near 41.</p></div><h3>How NULLs propagate through calculations</h3><p>NULL is not merely a marker; it actively spreads through arithmetic and logic, and understanding this propagation prevents subtle bugs. Any arithmetic expression involving NULL yields NULL: 100 + NULL is NULL, not 100. This means a derived column like total = price + tax silently becomes NULL for every row where tax is missing, quietly erasing data you thought you had. Functions exist to control this - <span class='keyterm'>COALESCE</span> returns the first non-NULL argument from a list, so COALESCE(tax, 0) substitutes zero where tax is missing, and the database-specific ISNULL or IFNULL do the same for a single value. Using COALESCE deliberately at the point of calculation is how you decide whether a missing value should be treated as zero, as a default, or left as genuinely unknown - a decision that should be conscious rather than accidental.</p><h3>Why disguised missing values are the worst kind</h3><p>Of all missingness, the disguised placeholder is the most insidious because it defeats the very tools meant to catch missing data. A proper NULL is invisible to SUM and AVG (they skip it) and visible to IS NULL checks, so it behaves predictably. A placeholder like 999, -1, or 'N/A' does the opposite: it is invisible to NULL checks (it is not NULL) yet fully visible to aggregates (it is a real value), so it silently poisons every average, sum, and chart while passing every completeness test. The defense is active profiling - examining the minimum, maximum, and frequency distribution of each column for implausible spikes - because a histogram with a tall bar at exactly 999 or a minimum of -1 on a quantity column is the signature of a disguised missing value. Converting these placeholders to real NULLs early is one of the highest-value cleansing steps, and recognizing the pattern is squarely on the exam.</p>"},
  {heading:"Duplication and Redundancy", body:"<p><span class='keyterm'>Duplication</span> - the same logical record appearing more than once - is one of the most damaging data quality problems because it inflates counts, double-counts revenue, and skews every aggregate. <span class='keyterm'>Redundancy</span> is the related storage of the same information in multiple places. The exam tests both the detection of duplicates and the judgment of when redundancy is a problem versus a deliberate design choice.</p><h3>Exact versus fuzzy duplicates</h3><p>An <span class='keyterm'>exact duplicate</span> is a row identical to another across all relevant columns - the same order imported twice. These are straightforward to find and remove. Far harder are <span class='keyterm'>fuzzy</span> (or near) duplicates: records that refer to the same real-world entity but differ in formatting, spelling, or completeness. \"Robert Smith, 123 Main St\" and \"Bob Smith, 123 Main Street\" are almost certainly the same person, yet no exact match will catch them. Resolving fuzzy duplicates is the discipline of <span class='keyterm'>entity resolution</span> (or record linkage / deduplication), and it relies on similarity scoring rather than equality.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Type</th><th>Detection</th><th>Example</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Exact duplicate</td><td>GROUP BY / DISTINCT / equality</td><td>Order #1001 imported twice</td></tr><tr><td>Fuzzy duplicate</td><td>Similarity / matching rules</td><td>\"Bob Smith\" vs \"Robert Smith\"</td></tr><tr><td>Partial duplicate</td><td>Key matches, other fields differ</td><td>Same email, two different phones</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Detecting duplicates in SQL</h3><p>The standard technique counts rows per candidate key and flags any group with more than one member:</p><pre>SELECT email, COUNT(*) AS cnt\nFROM customers\nGROUP BY email\nHAVING COUNT(*) > 1;</pre><p>To find rows duplicated across several columns, group by all of them. To <em>remove</em> duplicates while keeping one copy, modern SQL uses a window function to rank rows within each duplicate group and delete all but the first:</p><pre>WITH ranked AS (\n  SELECT *, ROW_NUMBER() OVER (\n    PARTITION BY email ORDER BY created_at\n  ) AS rn\n  FROM customers\n)\nDELETE FROM ranked WHERE rn > 1;</pre><h3>Deduplication in pandas</h3><pre>df.duplicated().sum()              # how many exact dup rows\ndf = df.drop_duplicates()          # remove exact dups\ndf = df.drop_duplicates(subset=['email'], keep='first')  # by key</pre><h3>Redundancy: bug or feature?</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Redundancy</span> is the same data stored in more than one place. In a normalized transactional database, redundancy is a defect that <span class='keyterm'>normalization</span> exists to eliminate, because duplicated facts can fall out of sync (one copy of a customer's address gets updated, the other does not - an <em>update anomaly</em>). But redundancy is sometimes deliberate. <span class='keyterm'>Denormalization</span> intentionally duplicates data in analytic warehouses to avoid expensive joins and speed up reads. So redundancy in an OLTP system is usually a problem to remove, while controlled redundancy in an OLAP star schema is a performance choice.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p><strong>Exact</strong> duplicates yield to DISTINCT / GROUP BY...HAVING COUNT(*) &gt; 1 / drop_duplicates. <strong>Fuzzy</strong> duplicates (\"Bob\" vs \"Robert\") require similarity matching, not equality. Redundancy in a transactional database is a defect normalization removes; deliberate redundancy (<em>denormalization</em>) in a warehouse is a valid speed optimization. Don't confuse the two.</p></div><h3>The cost of unresolved duplicates</h3><p>Duplicates corrupt analysis in concrete ways. A duplicated order row inflates revenue and order counts. A duplicated customer splits one person's history across two profiles, breaking lifetime-value and churn calculations. A duplicated event double-counts conversions, making a marketing campaign look twice as effective as it was. Because these errors compound through every downstream aggregate, deduplication is one of the highest-leverage cleansing steps.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>A retailer's loyalty program reports 1.4 million members, but marketing's mailings bounce at a strange rate. Profiling reveals many customers enrolled twice - once as \"Jennifer\" and once as \"Jen\" with the same address and phone. Exact-match dedup misses them; a fuzzy-matching rule on normalized name plus address plus phone collapses the pairs, dropping the true count to 1.1 million and fixing the inflated engagement metrics.</p></div><h3>Fuzzy matching techniques in practice</h3><p>Resolving fuzzy duplicates relies on <span class='keyterm'>similarity scoring</span> rather than equality, and several techniques recur. <span class='keyterm'>Edit distance</span> (Levenshtein distance) counts the single-character insertions, deletions, and substitutions needed to turn one string into another, so \"Jon\" and \"John\" differ by one and score as highly similar. <span class='keyterm'>Phonetic algorithms</span> like Soundex and Metaphone encode words by how they sound, matching \"Smith\" with \"Smyth.\" <span class='keyterm'>Normalization before comparison</span> - lowercasing, trimming, stripping punctuation, and expanding abbreviations (\"St.\" to \"Street\") - dramatically improves match rates before any scoring runs.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Technique</th><th>How it matches</th><th>Example</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Edit distance (Levenshtein)</td><td>Counts single-character edits between strings</td><td>\"Jon\" vs \"John\" (distance 1)</td></tr><tr><td>Phonetic (Soundex, Metaphone)</td><td>Encodes words by how they sound</td><td>\"Smith\" vs \"Smyth\"</td></tr><tr><td>Normalization before comparison</td><td>Lowercase, trim, strip punctuation, expand abbreviations</td><td>\"St.\" to \"Street\"</td></tr></tbody></table><p> Real entity-resolution pipelines combine several signals: a match might require a high name-similarity score <em>and</em> an identical phone or email, to avoid merging two genuinely different people who happen to share a common name. The key exam point is that fuzzy duplicates demand these similarity methods because exact equality, the basis of DISTINCT and GROUP BY, will never catch them.</p><h3>Choosing the surviving record</h3><p>When duplicates are found, deduplication is not just deletion - it is a <em>merge</em> decision about which record (or which combination of fields) survives. Common survivorship rules keep the most recently updated record, the most complete record (fewest NULLs), or the record from the most authoritative source system; a more sophisticated approach builds a \"golden record\" by taking the best non-NULL value for each field across all duplicates. This is the bridge from deduplication to <span class='keyterm'>master data management</span>, the governance discipline (covered in Domain 5) of maintaining one authoritative version of each key entity. The choice of survivorship rule should reflect the business meaning of the data, and it should be documented so the outcome is defensible.</p><h3>A defensible deduplication process</h3><p>Sound deduplication follows a repeatable order: define what makes two records the \"same\" (the matching key or rule), profile to quantify the duplicate rate, choose which record to keep when duplicates are found (the most recent, the most complete, or a merged survivor), and document the rule so the process is auditable and reproducible.</p><ol><li><strong>Define sameness</strong> - the matching key or rule that makes two records the same.</li><li><strong>Profile</strong> - quantify the duplicate rate.</li><li><strong>Choose the survivor</strong> - most recent, most complete, or a merged golden record.</li><li><strong>Document the rule</strong> - so the process is auditable and reproducible.</li></ol><p> Deleting duplicates without recording the rule risks both removing legitimate records and being unable to defend the row counts later - and once real records are wrongly merged or deleted, recovering them is far harder than preventing the loss with a careful, logged process.</p>"},
  {heading:"Outliers and Identifying Invalid Data", body:"<p>An <span class='keyterm'>outlier</span> is a data point that lies far from the bulk of the data. <span class='keyterm'>Invalid data</span> is a value that violates a rule - an impossible age, a future birth date, a negative quantity. The two overlap but are not the same, and the exam tests your judgment about which outliers are errors to fix and which are genuine signal to keep.</p><h3>Outlier versus invalid: a crucial distinction</h3><p>Not every outlier is wrong, and not every error is an outlier. A CEO's salary is a legitimate outlier in an employee dataset - real, important, and not to be deleted. A recorded human age of 207 is invalid data - it violates the rule that ages fall in a plausible range. The analyst's job is to investigate outliers, not reflexively remove them, because outliers can represent the most important cases (fraud, system failures, your best customers) or mere data-entry typos.</p><table><thead><tr><th></th><th>Outlier</th><th>Invalid data</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Definition</td><td>Far from the bulk of values</td><td>Violates a rule or constraint</td></tr><tr><td>Always wrong?</td><td>No - may be real signal</td><td>Yes - by definition impossible</td></tr><tr><td>Example</td><td>A 2-million-dollar order</td><td>Age = 207, negative quantity</td></tr><tr><td>Action</td><td>Investigate before deciding</td><td>Correct or remove</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Statistical methods for detecting outliers</h3><p>Two standard methods appear on the exam. The <span class='keyterm'>IQR method</span> uses the interquartile range: compute the first quartile (Q1) and third quartile (Q3), let IQR = Q3 - Q1, and flag any value below Q1 - 1.5 x IQR or above Q3 + 1.5 x IQR as an outlier. This is the logic behind the whiskers of a <span class='keyterm'>box plot</span>, which is the classic visual for spotting outliers. The <span class='keyterm'>z-score method</span> measures how many standard deviations a value sits from the mean; values with a z-score beyond roughly +/-3 are commonly flagged. The IQR method is robust because quartiles are not distorted by extreme values, whereas the z-score relies on the mean and standard deviation, which the outliers themselves can inflate.</p><table><thead><tr><th></th><th>IQR method</th><th>Z-score method</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Flags values</td><td>Below Q1 - 1.5xIQR or above Q3 + 1.5xIQR</td><td>Beyond roughly +/-3 standard deviations</td></tr><tr><td>Based on</td><td>Quartiles (Q1, Q3)</td><td>Mean and standard deviation</td></tr><tr><td>Visual</td><td>Box plot whiskers</td><td>Normal-curve tails</td></tr><tr><td>Robustness</td><td>Robust to extremes</td><td>Distorted by the very outliers it seeks</td></tr></tbody></table><pre>-- IQR-style flag in SQL (using percentiles)\nSELECT order_total\nFROM orders\nWHERE order_total > (\n  SELECT PERCENTILE_CONT(0.75) WITHIN GROUP (ORDER BY order_total)\n       + 1.5 * (PERCENTILE_CONT(0.75) WITHIN GROUP (ORDER BY order_total)\n              - PERCENTILE_CONT(0.25) WITHIN GROUP (ORDER BY order_total))\n  FROM orders\n);</pre><pre># z-score outlier flag in pandas\nfrom scipy import stats\nimport numpy as np\nz = np.abs(stats.zscore(df['order_total']))\noutliers = df[z > 3]</pre><h3>Detecting invalid data with rules</h3><p>Invalid data is caught by <span class='keyterm'>validation rules</span> and constraints rather than statistics. Range checks (age between 0 and 120), domain checks (status must be one of a known set), format checks (email matches a pattern), and cross-field checks (ship_date must not precede order_date) each catch a class of impossible values.</p><ul><li><em>Range check</em> - the value falls within allowed bounds (age between 0 and 120).</li><li><em>Domain check</em> - the value is one of a known set (status).</li><li><em>Format check</em> - the value matches a required pattern (email).</li><li><em>Cross-field check</em> - related fields agree (ship_date not before order_date).</li></ul><p> Where outlier detection is statistical and probabilistic, invalid-data detection is deterministic - the value either satisfies the rule or it does not.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>An <strong>outlier</strong> is far from the rest but may be real - investigate, don't auto-delete. <strong>Invalid data</strong> violates a defined rule (age 207, negative price) and should be corrected or removed. For detection, the <strong>IQR method</strong> (1.5 x IQR fences, box plot whiskers) is robust to extremes, while the <strong>z-score</strong> (beyond +/-3) assumes a roughly normal distribution and can be distorted by the very outliers it seeks.</p></div><h3>What to do with a confirmed outlier</h3><p>Once investigated, an outlier has several legitimate treatments. If it is a verified error, correct or remove it. If it is real but distorting an analysis, you may <em>cap</em> it (a technique called <span class='keyterm'>winsorizing</span>, replacing extremes with the nearest acceptable percentile), <em>transform</em> the data (a log transform compresses a long tail), or <em>segment</em> it out and analyze it separately. What you should not do is silently delete real outliers to make a chart prettier - that is data manipulation, not cleansing.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>A box plot of daily transaction amounts shows a point at 2 million dollars, far beyond the upper whisker. Rather than delete it, the analyst investigates and finds it was a legitimate bulk corporate purchase - real signal, not error. The same dataset, however, contains several transactions of -50 dollars, which violate the rule that amounts are non-negative; those are invalid data caused by a refund-coding bug and are corrected at the source.</p></div><h3>Univariate, bivariate, and contextual outliers</h3><p>Outliers come in more than one form, and recognizing the type guides detection. A <span class='keyterm'>univariate outlier</span> is extreme on a single variable - an income of ten million in a table of ordinary salaries - and is what IQR and z-score methods catch. A <span class='keyterm'>multivariate outlier</span> is unremarkable on each variable alone but impossible in combination: a height of 200 cm is fine and a weight of 40 kg is fine, but together they describe a person who almost certainly does not exist, so the <em>pair</em> is the anomaly. A <span class='keyterm'>contextual outlier</span> is extreme only in context: a temperature of 30 degrees is normal in summer but a glaring anomaly in winter, so it is the combination with season that flags it. Simple single-column tests miss multivariate and contextual outliers entirely, which is why scatter plots, cross-field validation rules, and domain knowledge remain essential alongside the statistical methods.</p><h3>Visualizing outliers</h3><p>Charts are often faster than formulas for spotting anomalies, and the exam pairs specific visuals with this task. The <span class='keyterm'>box plot</span> is the canonical outlier chart: its box spans Q1 to Q3, its whiskers extend to the 1.5-IQR fences, and any point beyond a whisker is drawn individually as a flagged outlier. A <span class='keyterm'>histogram</span> reveals disguised missing values and skew as suspicious spikes or long tails. A <span class='keyterm'>scatter plot</span> exposes multivariate outliers as points sitting far from the main cloud, which no single-variable test would catch. Reaching for the right chart turns outlier detection from a calculation into a glance, and recognizing which chart suits which job is a tested skill that also connects forward to the visualization material in Domain 4.</p><h3>Context decides everything</h3><p>The recurring lesson is that outlier handling demands domain context. A heart rate of 30 is an outlier that might be an error - or might be a real, clinically critical reading on a sleeping athlete. The exam rewards the answer that <em>investigates and understands</em> the outlier before acting, and that distinguishes a statistically extreme but valid value from a value that breaks a hard business rule. Deleting outliers to tidy a chart, when those outliers are real, is not cleansing but distortion - the kind of choice that produces a prettier graph and a wronger conclusion.</p>"},
  {heading:"Completeness and Validation Methods", body:"<p><span class='keyterm'>Completeness</span> asks whether all the data that should be present actually is - no missing records, no missing fields, no truncated loads. <span class='keyterm'>Validation</span> is the broader set of checks that confirm data is accurate, conformant, and trustworthy before it is used. Together they are the gatekeepers of data quality, and the exam tests the specific check types and quality dimensions by name.</p><h3>The dimensions of data quality</h3><p>Data quality is conventionally measured across several <em>dimensions</em>, and completeness is one of them. Knowing the full set helps you name precisely what is wrong with a dataset.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Dimension</th><th>Question it answers</th><th>Example failure</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Completeness</td><td>Is all expected data present?</td><td>30% of phone numbers blank</td></tr><tr><td>Accuracy</td><td>Does it reflect reality?</td><td>Address is wrong</td></tr><tr><td>Consistency</td><td>Does it agree across systems?</td><td>CRM and billing show different totals</td></tr><tr><td>Validity</td><td>Does it conform to rules/format?</td><td>Email missing the @ symbol</td></tr><tr><td>Uniqueness</td><td>No unintended duplicates?</td><td>Same customer twice</td></tr><tr><td>Timeliness</td><td>Is it current enough?</td><td>Yesterday's prices on a live dashboard</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Measuring completeness</h3><p>Completeness is quantified at two levels. <em>Column completeness</em> is the percentage of non-NULL values in a field - if 9,700 of 10,000 customers have an email, the email column is 97 percent complete. <em>Record completeness</em> asks whether entire rows are missing - did the nightly load bring in all 10,000 orders, or only 9,400 because the job failed partway? A <span class='keyterm'>row count reconciliation</span> (comparing source and target counts) is the standard guard against truncated loads.</p><pre>-- Completeness percentage per column\nSELECT\n  ROUND(100.0 * COUNT(email)  / COUNT(*), 1) AS email_complete_pct,\n  ROUND(100.0 * COUNT(phone)  / COUNT(*), 1) AS phone_complete_pct\nFROM customers;</pre><h3>Validation check types</h3><p>Validation applies targeted rules to catch bad data, and the exam expects you to recognize each type by its behavior.</p><ul><li><span class='keyterm'>Range check</span> - value falls within allowed bounds (age 0-120, percentage 0-100).</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Format check</span> - value matches a required pattern (email, phone, postal code), often via regex.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Type check</span> - value is the correct data type (a number where a number is expected).</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Consistency / cross-field check</span> - related fields agree (ship_date &gt;= order_date).</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Uniqueness check</span> - a key has no duplicates.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Referential integrity check</span> - a foreign key points to a real parent row.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Presence / required check</span> - a mandatory field is not NULL.</li></ul><h3>Where validation happens</h3><p>Validation can occur at several points, and earlier is cheaper. <span class='keyterm'>Front-end validation</span> in a form rejects bad input before it is ever stored. <span class='keyterm'>Database constraints</span> (NOT NULL, CHECK, UNIQUE, FOREIGN KEY) enforce rules at write time. <span class='keyterm'>Pipeline validation</span> checks data as it moves through ETL/ELT. And <span class='keyterm'>profiling</span> validates data after the fact during exploration. A robust program layers these so a bad value has to slip past several gates to cause harm.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>Match the failure to the dimension: blanks = <em>completeness</em>, wrong-but-well-formed = <em>accuracy</em>, disagreement across systems = <em>consistency</em>, breaks a format rule = <em>validity</em>, stale = <em>timeliness</em>, duplicates = <em>uniqueness</em>. For checks, a <strong>range check</strong> bounds a number, a <strong>format check</strong> matches a pattern (often regex), and a <strong>referential integrity check</strong> ensures a foreign key has a matching parent.</p></div><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>A nightly load is expected to bring 50,000 transactions, but a reconciliation report shows only 47,300 landed - a completeness failure from a job that timed out. Separately, 1,200 rows passed the load but carry email values with no @ symbol, a validity failure a format check should have caught at entry. The analyst fixes the truncated load by re-running it and adds a front-end format check to stop malformed emails at the source.</p></div><h3>Validation versus verification</h3><p>The exam sometimes distinguishes two similar-sounding terms. <span class='keyterm'>Validation</span> asks whether data conforms to defined rules and formats - is this a well-formed email, does this age fall in range, does this foreign key point somewhere real? It checks the data against expectations <em>internal</em> to the system. <span class='keyterm'>Verification</span> asks whether the data is actually <em>true</em> - does this address really exist, is this the customer's real phone number? - which usually requires comparison against an external source of truth. A value can be perfectly valid (a correctly formatted phone number) yet unverified (it belongs to no one). Validation is cheap and automatable; verification is more expensive and often requires a third-party reference or human confirmation. Knowing that validation checks <em>form</em> while verification checks <em>truth</em> clarifies why passing every format check still does not guarantee correct data.</p><table><thead><tr><th></th><th>Validation</th><th>Verification</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Question</td><td>Does it conform to rules/format?</td><td>Is it actually true?</td></tr><tr><td>Checks against</td><td>Expectations internal to the system</td><td>An external source of truth</td></tr><tr><td>Example</td><td>Well-formed email, age in range</td><td>The address really exists</td></tr><tr><td>Cost</td><td>Cheap and automatable</td><td>Expensive; often needs a reference or human</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Building validation into the pipeline as gates</h3><p>The most resilient approach treats validation as a series of <em>gates</em> that data must pass, with each failure routed to a quarantine or error table rather than silently dropped or, worse, silently admitted. A row that fails a required-field check, a range check, or a referential-integrity check is set aside with a reason code, so the pipeline can report \"1,200 rows rejected: 800 invalid email format, 400 missing customer_id\" instead of producing a result that is quietly short by 1,200 rows. This pattern - validate, quarantine, report, and reconcile - turns data quality from an invisible erosion into a measured, monitored property. It also produces the audit trail Domain 5 governance requires, because every rejected row and the rule that rejected it is recorded. A pipeline that merely loads whatever it can and ignores the rest is the most common cause of the slow, silent quality decay that eventually undermines trust in a dataset.</p><h3>Completeness versus accuracy</h3><p>A subtle but tested point: complete data is not necessarily accurate, and accurate data is not necessarily complete. A customer table can be 100 percent complete - every field filled - yet riddled with wrong addresses (an accuracy failure). Conversely, every present value can be perfectly accurate while 40 percent of records are missing entirely (a completeness failure). Strong validation tests for both, because each masks the other if you measure only one.</p>"},
  {heading:"String Manipulation and Regular Expressions", body:"<p>Text is the messiest data type, and <span class='keyterm'>string manipulation</span> - trimming, splitting, replacing, padding, and changing case - is core cleansing work. When patterns get complex, <span class='keyterm'>regular expressions</span> (regex) provide a compact language for matching and extracting text. The Data+ exam tests both the common string functions and the ability to read basic regex.</p><h3>Common string functions</h3><p>Nearly every SQL dialect and analytics language offers the same family of string operations, though names vary slightly.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Operation</th><th>SQL</th><th>pandas</th><th>Purpose</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Remove whitespace</td><td>TRIM(col)</td><td>str.strip()</td><td>Strip leading/trailing spaces</td></tr><tr><td>Change case</td><td>UPPER / LOWER</td><td>str.upper / str.lower</td><td>Standardize case</td></tr><tr><td>Substring</td><td>SUBSTRING(col,1,3)</td><td>str[:3]</td><td>Extract part of a string</td></tr><tr><td>Replace</td><td>REPLACE(col,'-','')</td><td>str.replace('-','')</td><td>Swap text</td></tr><tr><td>Length</td><td>LENGTH(col)</td><td>str.len()</td><td>Count characters</td></tr><tr><td>Concatenate</td><td>CONCAT / ||</td><td>+ operator</td><td>Join strings</td></tr><tr><td>Split</td><td>SPLIT_PART</td><td>str.split()</td><td>Break on a delimiter</td></tr></tbody></table><p>These primitives solve the bulk of text cleansing. TRIM removes the invisible leading and trailing spaces that cause \" California \" to fail to match \"California\". UPPER or LOWER collapse case differences so \"USA\" and \"usa\" group together. REPLACE strips formatting characters from phone numbers and IDs. The exam frequently presents a messy value and asks which function produces the cleaned result.</p><pre>-- Standardize a messy state field\nSELECT UPPER(TRIM(state)) AS state_clean FROM addresses;\n-- Strip dashes from a phone number\nSELECT REPLACE(phone, '-', '') AS phone_digits FROM contacts;</pre><h3>Regular expressions</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>regular expression</span> is a pattern that describes a set of strings. Regex is the right tool when a simple function cannot express the rule - validating an email, extracting all numbers from a free-text field, or finding values that match a complex format. The core syntax the exam may show:</p><table><thead><tr><th>Token</th><th>Matches</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>.</td><td>Any single character</td></tr><tr><td>\\d</td><td>A digit (0-9)</td></tr><tr><td>\\w</td><td>A word character (letter, digit, underscore)</td></tr><tr><td>\\s</td><td>Whitespace</td></tr><tr><td>^ / $</td><td>Start / end of string</td></tr><tr><td>* / + / ?</td><td>Zero+, one+, zero-or-one</td></tr><tr><td>{n,m}</td><td>Between n and m repetitions</td></tr><tr><td>[abc]</td><td>Any one of a, b, c</td></tr><tr><td>( )</td><td>A capture group for extraction</td></tr></tbody></table><p>Putting tokens together yields practical patterns. A US ZIP code is <strong>^\\d{5}(-\\d{4})?$</strong> - five digits, optionally followed by a hyphen and four more. A simple email check is <strong>^[\\w.]+@[\\w.]+\\.\\w{2,}$</strong> - word characters and dots, an @, more of the same, a dot, and a two-plus-letter top-level domain.</p><pre># pandas: keep only rows whose ZIP matches the pattern\nvalid = df[df['zip'].str.match(r'^\\d{5}(-\\d{4})?$')]\n# extract the area code from a phone number\ndf['area_code'] = df['phone'].str.extract(r'\\((\\d{3})\\)')</pre><pre>-- regex in PostgreSQL: find emails missing an @\nSELECT email FROM users WHERE email !~ '^[\\w.]+@[\\w.]+\\.\\w{2,}$';</pre><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>For simple, fixed edits (strip spaces, change case, remove dashes) reach for string functions - <strong>TRIM</strong>, <strong>UPPER/LOWER</strong>, <strong>REPLACE</strong>. For pattern matching, extraction, or validation use <strong>regex</strong>: <em>\\d</em> is a digit, <em>+</em> is one-or-more, <em>^</em> and <em>$</em> anchor the start and end, and parentheses ( ) capture a group for extraction. If a question asks to validate a format like an email or ZIP, the answer is a regex.</p></div><h3>Why string cleansing matters so much</h3><p>Text inconsistencies are a leading cause of failed joins and split groups. \"  IBM\", \"IBM \", \"ibm\", and \"I.B.M.\" are four spellings of one company that will not group or join until standardized. A single untrimmed space silently breaks an equality match, producing a phantom \"missing\" record. Because so many keys and categories are text, disciplined string standardization - trim, case-fold, strip punctuation, then match - is among the highest-impact cleansing routines.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>A sales report shows \"California\" and \"california\" and \" CA \" as three separate regions, splitting the state's revenue across three rows. The analyst applies UPPER(TRIM(state)) and a lookup that maps both \"CALIFORNIA\" and \"CA\" to a canonical code, collapsing the three into one correct total. A separate free-text comments field is mined with the regex \\d{3}-\\d{3}-\\d{4} to extract phone numbers customers typed into the wrong box.</p></div><h3>Choosing string functions versus regex</h3><p>A practical decision the exam tests is when a simple string function suffices and when regex is warranted. If the edit is fixed and positional - strip the leading and trailing spaces, uppercase the whole value, replace every literal dash with nothing, take the first three characters - a plain function (TRIM, UPPER, REPLACE, SUBSTRING) is clearer, faster, and easier to maintain. Reach for regex only when the rule involves a <em>pattern</em> rather than a fixed string: validating that a value looks like an email, extracting whatever digits appear inside arbitrary text, splitting on any run of whitespace, or matching one of several formats at once. Overusing regex for jobs a simple function handles makes code harder to read and debug; underusing it forces brittle chains of REPLACE calls where one pattern would do. Matching the tool to the shape of the rule is the skill.</p><h3>Common regex patterns worth recognizing</h3><p>A handful of patterns appear so often that recognizing them on sight is valuable. <strong>^\\d{3}-\\d{2}-\\d{4}$</strong> matches a US Social Security number; <strong>^\\(?\\d{3}\\)?[-. ]?\\d{3}[-. ]?\\d{4}$</strong> tolerates the many ways people format a phone number; <strong>^\\d{4}-\\d{2}-\\d{2}$</strong> matches an ISO date; and a character class like <strong>[^a-zA-Z0-9 ]</strong> matches any character that is <em>not</em> a letter, digit, or space, which is the basis for stripping punctuation. These recurring patterns are worth recognizing on sight:</p><ul><li><strong>^\\d{3}-\\d{2}-\\d{4}$</strong> - a US Social Security number.</li><li><strong>^\\(?\\d{3}\\)?[-. ]?\\d{3}[-. ]?\\d{4}$</strong> - a phone number in its many formats.</li><li><strong>^\\d{4}-\\d{2}-\\d{2}$</strong> - an ISO date.</li><li><strong>[^a-zA-Z0-9 ]</strong> - any character that is <em>not</em> a letter, digit, or space (for stripping punctuation).</li></ul><p>The caret inside square brackets, as in [^...], means negation - \"any character except these\" - which is a different meaning from the caret at the start of a pattern, where ^ anchors the start of the string. That dual meaning of the caret is a classic source of confusion the exam can exploit, so read its position carefully.</p><h3>Greedy matching and common pitfalls</h3><p>Regex has subtleties the exam occasionally hints at. Quantifiers are <em>greedy</em> by default, matching as much as possible, which can over-capture; adding ? makes them lazy. Special characters like the dot, plus, and parentheses must be <em>escaped</em> with a backslash to match literally (\\. matches a real period). And regex flavors differ slightly across SQL, Python, and JavaScript, so a pattern that works in one may need minor adjustment in another - a reason to test patterns against real sample data before trusting them in a pipeline.</p>"},
  {heading:"Type Conversion and Standardization", body:"<p><span class='keyterm'>Type conversion</span> (casting) changes a value's data type - text to number, string to date, number to text. <span class='keyterm'>Standardization</span> brings inconsistent values into a single consistent form - one date format, one unit, one set of category labels. Both are foundational transformation skills, and the exam tests when a conversion is needed and what goes wrong when it fails.</p><h3>Why type matters</h3><p>A value's <em>type</em> determines what operations are legal and how it sorts. The string \"100\" and the number 100 look identical but behave differently: numbers sort numerically (2 &lt; 10), while strings sort lexicographically (\"10\" &lt; \"2\" because '1' precedes '2'). You cannot sum a column of numbers stored as text, and you cannot do date arithmetic on dates stored as strings. This is why numeric and date fields imported as text from CSVs must be converted before analysis - a step the exam frequently tests.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Stored as</th><th>Problem</th><th>Fix</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>\"1,234.50\" (text)</td><td>Can't sum or average</td><td>Strip commas, CAST to numeric</td></tr><tr><td>\"03/04/2025\" (text)</td><td>Can't sort by date or compute age</td><td>Parse to a DATE type</td></tr><tr><td>\"TRUE\"/\"FALSE\" (text)</td><td>Can't filter as boolean</td><td>Convert to boolean</td></tr><tr><td>1 / 0 (numeric flag)</td><td>Ambiguous meaning</td><td>Map to boolean/category</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Explicit versus implicit conversion</h3><p>An <span class='keyterm'>explicit conversion</span> is one you request directly with CAST or CONVERT. An <span class='keyterm'>implicit conversion</span> happens automatically when the engine coerces a type to make an operation work (comparing a text column to a number). Implicit conversions are convenient but risky: they can silently change behavior, hurt performance by preventing index use, or fail unexpectedly. Best practice is to convert <em>explicitly</em> so the intent is clear and the failure point is predictable.</p><table><thead><tr><th></th><th>Explicit conversion</th><th>Implicit conversion</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>How it happens</td><td>Requested directly with CAST/CONVERT</td><td>Engine coerces a type automatically</td></tr><tr><td>Intent</td><td>Clear and deliberate</td><td>Hidden in the comparison</td></tr><tr><td>Risk</td><td>Predictable failure point</td><td>Silent behavior change, lost index use, surprise failures</td></tr></tbody></table><pre>-- Explicit casts in SQL\nSELECT CAST(price_text AS DECIMAL(10,2)) AS price,\n       CAST(order_date_text AS DATE)     AS order_date\nFROM raw_orders;</pre><pre># pandas type conversion\ndf['price'] = pd.to_numeric(df['price'], errors='coerce')   # bad -> NaN\ndf['order_date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['order_date'], format='%m/%d/%Y')\ndf['is_active'] = df['is_active'].astype('bool')</pre><h3>When conversion fails</h3><p>Conversion fails when a value cannot be represented in the target type - casting \"N/A\" to a number, or \"2025-13-45\" to a date. You must decide the failure policy: error out (stop and fix the source), or coerce the bad value to NULL and continue (pandas errors='coerce' does this, turning unconvertible values into NaN). The exam expects awareness that silent coercion can mask data problems - a column that quietly fills with NULLs after a cast is a red flag that the source data is dirtier than assumed.</p><h3>Standardization</h3><p>Standardization is conversion's broader cousin: making semantically equal values <em>look</em> equal. Its main forms:</p><ul><li><span class='keyterm'>Date standardization</span> - one canonical format, ideally ISO 8601 (YYYY-MM-DD), to end the MM/DD vs DD/MM ambiguity.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Unit standardization</span> - one unit system (all metric, or all dollars), converting where sources disagree.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Categorical standardization</span> - one label per concept (\"USA\", \"U.S.A.\", \"United States\" all map to a single code).</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Case and format standardization</span> - consistent capitalization and punctuation, often via the string functions from the prior section.</li></ul><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>Numbers and dates imported as <em>text</em> must be <strong>cast</strong> before math or sorting - \"10\" &lt; \"2\" as text but 10 &gt; 2 as numbers. Prefer <strong>explicit</strong> CAST/CONVERT over relying on implicit coercion. For dates, standardize to <strong>ISO 8601 (YYYY-MM-DD)</strong> to remove MM/DD vs DD/MM ambiguity. Watch for casts that silently produce NULLs - that signals dirty source values.</p></div><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>An analyst imports a CSV where the date column reads \"03/04/2025\". Half the source systems meant March 4 and half meant April 3, and because the field was stored as text, no one noticed the dates sorted alphabetically rather than chronologically. The analyst parses the column to a true DATE type using each source's known format, standardizes everything to ISO 8601, and the timeline finally sorts and filters correctly.</p></div><h3>Categorical standardization with lookup tables</h3><p>The most common standardization task in business data is collapsing many spellings of one category into a single canonical value, and the durable way to do it is a <span class='keyterm'>lookup table</span> (or mapping table) rather than an ever-growing chain of CASE statements. A two-column reference table that maps every observed variant - \"USA\", \"U.S.A.\", \"United States\", \"US\", \"America\" - to one standard code lets you join incoming data against it to produce the clean value, and it makes the mapping itself <em>data</em> that can be reviewed, versioned, and extended without rewriting queries. This approach scales to thousands of variants where inline logic would become unmanageable, and it concentrates the business rule in one auditable place. When a scenario describes dozens of inconsistent category labels that must be unified, a lookup/mapping table is the professional answer.</p><h3>Datetime conversion subtleties</h3><p>Dates and times carry more traps than any other type. Beyond the MM/DD versus DD/MM ambiguity, you must reckon with <em>time zones</em> - a timestamp without a zone is ambiguous, and naively comparing two timestamps captured in different zones produces wrong intervals. The recommended practice is to store timestamps in <span class='keyterm'>UTC</span> and convert to local time only for display. Two-digit years are another hazard, since \"25\" might mean 1925 or 2025 depending on a pivot rule you cannot see. And parsing requires telling the function the <em>exact</em> input format (the %m/%d/%Y pattern in the pandas example) so it does not guess wrong on ambiguous values. Because so much analysis is time-based - trends, cohorts, retention, seasonality - getting datetime conversion right is foundational, and silent date errors are among the hardest bugs to detect after the fact.</p><h3>The order of operations</h3><p>Standardization and conversion usually go hand in hand and in a sensible order: first clean the string (trim, strip thousands separators, fix obvious typos), then convert the type (cast to number or date), then standardize the form (canonical category label, ISO date, common unit). Doing them out of order - casting before stripping a stray comma, for instance - causes avoidable conversion failures. Getting this sequence right is what separates a pipeline that loads cleanly from one that drops thousands of rows to coercion errors.</p>"},
  {heading:"Scaling, Binning, and Clustering", body:"<p>Three transformation techniques reshape numeric data for analysis and modeling: <span class='keyterm'>scaling</span> puts variables on a common range, <span class='keyterm'>binning</span> converts continuous numbers into discrete categories, and <span class='keyterm'>clustering</span> groups similar records together. The exam tests what each does, why you would use it, and the difference between supervised labels and unsupervised grouping.</p><h3>Scaling (feature scaling)</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Scaling</span> transforms numeric variables so they share a comparable range, which matters when features have wildly different magnitudes - income in the tens of thousands versus age in the tens. Without scaling, a distance- or magnitude-sensitive method (clustering, k-nearest neighbors, gradient descent) is dominated by the large-magnitude variable. Two methods dominate:</p><table><thead><tr><th>Method</th><th>Formula idea</th><th>Resulting range</th><th>Use when</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Normalization (min-max)</td><td>(x - min) / (max - min)</td><td>0 to 1</td><td>Bounded range needed; no strong outliers</td></tr><tr><td>Standardization (z-score)</td><td>(x - mean) / std dev</td><td>Mean 0, std 1</td><td>Data roughly normal; outliers present</td></tr></tbody></table><p><span class='keyterm'>Min-max normalization</span> squeezes values into a fixed 0-to-1 band, which is intuitive but sensitive to outliers (one extreme value compresses everything else). <span class='keyterm'>Z-score standardization</span> recenters data to mean 0 and unit standard deviation, which handles outliers better and is the common default for many statistical methods. Note the terminology trap: \"normalization\" here means min-max scaling, a completely different concept from database <em>normalization</em> (eliminating redundancy).</p><pre># scaling in pandas / scikit-learn\nfrom sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler, StandardScaler\ndf['income_norm'] = MinMaxScaler().fit_transform(df[['income']])\ndf['income_z']    = StandardScaler().fit_transform(df[['income']])</pre><h3>Binning (discretization)</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Binning</span> (bucketing or discretization) converts a continuous variable into a set of discrete categories. Ages become \"18-25\", \"26-40\", \"41-65\", \"65+\"; incomes become \"low/medium/high\". Binning simplifies analysis, reduces the impact of small fluctuations and minor outliers, and makes patterns easier to chart and communicate. The tradeoff is lost precision - once binned, you can no longer recover the exact value. Two binning strategies recur, described below. Equal-frequency is better when data is skewed, because equal-width bins can leave some buckets nearly empty.</p><ul><li><span class='keyterm'>Equal-width</span> bins - span equal value ranges (every bin is 10 units wide).</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Equal-frequency</span> bins - each holds the same number of records (quartiles, deciles).</li></ul><pre>-- equal-width age bins in SQL with CASE\nSELECT customer_id,\n  CASE\n    WHEN age < 26 THEN '18-25'\n    WHEN age < 41 THEN '26-40'\n    WHEN age < 66 THEN '41-65'\n    ELSE '65+'\n  END AS age_group\nFROM customers;</pre><pre># pandas binning\ndf['age_group'] = pd.cut(df['age'], bins=[18,25,40,65,120],\n                         labels=['18-25','26-40','41-65','65+'])\ndf['income_q']  = pd.qcut(df['income'], q=4)  # equal-frequency quartiles</pre><h3>Clustering</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Clustering</span> is an <em>unsupervised</em> technique that groups records so that members of a group are more similar to one another than to members of other groups - without any predefined labels. The classic algorithm is <span class='keyterm'>k-means</span>, which partitions data into k groups by minimizing within-cluster distance. Clustering is the engine behind <em>customer segmentation</em>, anomaly grouping, and market basket analysis. Because it relies on distance, scaling the features first is essential - otherwise the variable with the largest raw range dominates the grouping.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p><strong>Scaling</strong> puts variables on a common range: <em>min-max normalization</em> -&gt; 0-1, <em>z-score standardization</em> -&gt; mean 0/std 1. \"Normalization\" here is min-max scaling, NOT database normalization. <strong>Binning</strong> turns continuous values into categories (age groups). <strong>Clustering</strong> is <em>unsupervised</em> grouping (no labels) - distinct from classification, which is supervised and uses known labels. Scale your features before clustering.</p></div><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>A marketing team wants to segment customers by spending and visit frequency. Spending ranges 0-50,000 while visits range 1-200, so the analyst first standardizes both to z-scores, then runs k-means clustering, which discovers three natural groups: occasional small spenders, frequent moderate spenders, and rare big spenders. Skipping the scaling step would have let raw spending dominate the distance calculation and produce meaningless clusters.</p></div><h3>Why scaling must respect the train/test boundary</h3><p>A subtle but important discipline when scaling for any model is that the scaling parameters - the min and max for normalization, or the mean and standard deviation for standardization - must be computed from the <em>training</em> data only and then applied to new data, never recomputed on the combined set. Computing them across the whole dataset, including data the model will later be evaluated on, leaks information about the test set into training and inflates the apparent performance. In scikit-learn this is why you call fit on the training set and merely transform the test set. Even outside formal modeling, the principle generalizes: scaling and binning thresholds derived from one population should be applied consistently to new data rather than silently recalculated, or the categories drift and become incomparable across time periods. This consistency requirement is part of what makes a transformation reproducible.</p><h3>One-hot encoding and preparing categories for analysis</h3><p>Just as continuous variables often need scaling, categorical variables often need <em>encoding</em> before they can enter many statistical methods, and the most common technique is <span class='keyterm'>one-hot encoding</span> - turning a single category column with values like \"red/green/blue\" into three binary indicator columns, one per category, each holding a 1 or 0. This lets methods that require numeric input use categorical information without falsely implying that the categories have a numeric order. A related choice, <span class='keyterm'>ordinal encoding</span>, assigns ordered integers and is appropriate only when the categories genuinely have a rank (small/medium/large). Choosing one-hot for unordered categories and ordinal for ranked ones prevents a model from inventing a meaningless order, and the distinction parallels the data-type and measurement-scale concepts from Domain 1.</p><h3>Clustering versus classification</h3><p>A distinction the exam tests: <span class='keyterm'>clustering</span> is unsupervised - you have no labels and the algorithm discovers groups. <span class='keyterm'>Classification</span> is supervised - you already have labeled examples (spam vs. not spam) and train a model to assign new records to those known classes. Binning resembles a manual, rule-based form of classification into ranges, whereas clustering finds groups you did not define in advance. Choosing the right one depends on whether you have known categories to assign to (classification) or are searching for structure you have not yet named (clustering).</p><table><thead><tr><th></th><th>Clustering</th><th>Classification</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Supervision</td><td>Unsupervised (no labels)</td><td>Supervised (labeled examples)</td></tr><tr><td>Goal</td><td>Discover groups not defined in advance</td><td>Assign records to known classes</td></tr><tr><td>Example</td><td>Customer segmentation with k-means</td><td>Spam vs. not-spam detection</td></tr></tbody></table>"},
  {heading:"Augmentation, Derived Variables, Parsing, and Exploding", body:"<p>Beyond cleaning what exists, analysts <em>create</em> new data from old. <span class='keyterm'>Data augmentation</span> enriches a dataset, <span class='keyterm'>derived variables</span> and <span class='keyterm'>calculated fields</span> compute new columns from existing ones, <span class='keyterm'>parsing</span> breaks compound values apart, and <span class='keyterm'>exploding</span> turns nested or multi-valued fields into separate rows. These constructive transformations often unlock the most analytical value, and the exam tests each by example.</p><h3>Derived variables and calculated fields</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>derived variable</span> (or calculated field) is a new column computed from other columns. Examples are everywhere: profit = revenue - cost; age = today - birth_date; full_name = first || ' ' || last; days_to_ship = ship_date - order_date; a price-per-unit ratio; a year extracted from a date. Calculated fields are the backbone of BI tools - Tableau \"calculated fields,\" Power BI \"measures\" and \"calculated columns,\" Excel formulas - and they let you answer questions the raw schema never anticipated.</p><pre>SELECT order_id,\n       revenue - cost                          AS profit,\n       ROUND((revenue - cost) / revenue, 3)    AS margin,\n       DATEDIFF(ship_date, order_date)         AS days_to_ship,\n       EXTRACT(YEAR FROM order_date)           AS order_year\nFROM orders;</pre><table><thead><tr><th>Derived field</th><th>Computed from</th><th>Business use</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Profit margin</td><td>(revenue - cost) / revenue</td><td>Profitability analysis</td></tr><tr><td>Age</td><td>current_date - birth_date</td><td>Demographic segmentation</td></tr><tr><td>Days to ship</td><td>ship_date - order_date</td><td>Fulfillment KPI</td></tr><tr><td>Day of week</td><td>From a date</td><td>Seasonality / staffing</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Parsing compound values</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Parsing</span> breaks a single field that packs multiple pieces of information into its components. A full name splits into first and last; a timestamp splits into date and time; a full address splits into street, city, state, and ZIP; a delimited code splits on its separator. Parsing is the inverse of concatenation and uses split or substring functions, often guided by a delimiter or a regex.</p><pre>-- parse first and last name on the space\nSELECT SPLIT_PART(full_name, ' ', 1) AS first_name,\n       SPLIT_PART(full_name, ' ', 2) AS last_name\nFROM contacts;</pre><pre># pandas: split and expand into new columns\ndf[['first','last']] = df['full_name'].str.split(' ', n=1, expand=True)</pre><h3>Exploding nested and multi-valued data</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Exploding</span> (or unnesting) transforms a field that holds <em>multiple values</em> into multiple rows, one per value - the opposite of aggregation. A common case is a column like tags = \"red,blue,green\" or a JSON array of order line items: exploding turns that one row into three, each with a single tag. This is essential when semi-structured data (JSON, arrays) must be flattened into tidy, one-value-per-cell tabular form for analysis.</p><pre># pandas explode a list column into rows\ndf['tags'] = df['tags'].str.split(',')\ndf = df.explode('tags')   # one row per tag</pre><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p><strong>Parsing</strong> splits one column into several columns (full name -&gt; first, last). <strong>Exploding</strong> splits one row into several rows (a comma list or JSON array -&gt; one value per row). A <strong>derived/calculated field</strong> computes a new column from existing ones (profit, age, days_to_ship). Don't confuse parsing (more columns) with exploding (more rows).</p></div><table><thead><tr><th>Transform</th><th>Changes</th><th>Example</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Parsing</td><td>One column into several columns</td><td>full_name -&gt; first, last</td></tr><tr><td>Exploding</td><td>One row into several rows</td><td>\"red,blue,green\" -&gt; three rows</td></tr><tr><td>Derived field</td><td>Adds one new computed column</td><td>profit = revenue - cost</td></tr><tr><td>Augmentation</td><td>Adds external information</td><td>Join ZIP-to-region lookup</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Data augmentation and enrichment</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Data augmentation</span> adds new information to a dataset, often from external sources. <span class='keyterm'>Enrichment</span> joins in reference data - appending demographic data by ZIP code, geocoding addresses into latitude/longitude, adding industry codes to companies, or mapping IP addresses to locations. Augmentation can also mean generating synthetic data to balance a dataset (oversampling a rare class) or, in machine learning, creating variations of training data. The unifying idea is increasing the analytical value of the data beyond what the raw source provided.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>An e-commerce table has one row per order with a single column listing all products as \"SKU-1;SKU-2;SKU-3\" and a customer's full mailing address in one field. The analyst <em>explodes</em> the product list so each SKU becomes its own row for line-item analysis, <em>parses</em> the address into city/state/ZIP columns, then <em>augments</em> by joining a ZIP-to-region lookup, and finally computes a <em>derived</em> profit-margin field. Each transformation adds analytical power the raw export lacked.</p></div><h3>Date and time feature extraction</h3><p>One of the most productive sources of derived variables is the humble timestamp, because a single datetime field secretly contains a dozen useful features. From one order_date you can derive the year, quarter, month, week, day of month, day of week, hour, whether it was a weekend, and whether it fell on a holiday - each a calculated field that unlocks a different analytical angle.</p><ul><li><strong>Day of week and hour</strong> - expose staffing and traffic patterns.</li><li><strong>Month and quarter</strong> - expose seasonality.</li><li><strong>Days since last purchase</strong> - powers churn and recency analysis.</li><li><strong>Weekend / holiday flags</strong> - separate ordinary days from exceptions.</li></ul><p>Day-of-week and hour expose staffing and traffic patterns; month and quarter expose seasonality; a derived \"days since last purchase\" powers churn and recency analysis. This is why date dimensions are a staple of data warehouses: pre-computing these date attributes once, into a reusable date dimension table, lets every report slice time consistently without re-deriving the same fields repeatedly. Recognizing that a timestamp is a rich feature source rather than a single value is a hallmark of mature data preparation.</p><h3>Tidy data as the goal of constructive transformation</h3><p>The unifying objective behind parsing, exploding, and deriving is reaching <span class='keyterm'>tidy data</span> - a structure where each variable is a column, each observation is a row, and each cell holds a single value. Compound fields (a full address in one column) violate the one-value-per-cell rule and must be parsed; multi-valued fields (a comma-separated tag list) violate it too and must be exploded; and missing useful variables are added through derivation and augmentation. Tidy data is not an aesthetic preference; it is the shape that makes filtering, grouping, joining, and charting straightforward, and most analysis tools assume it. When a dataset resists a simple GROUP BY or a clean chart, the root cause is frequently that it is not tidy - a value is buried inside a compound field or smeared across columns - and the remedy is exactly the constructive transformations of this section.</p><h3>Order and reversibility</h3><p>These constructive transforms compose in a logical order and most are reversible in principle. You typically parse and explode to get data into a clean tidy shape, then derive calculated fields on that clean base, then augment with external joins. Keeping the raw source alongside the derived columns preserves the ability to recompute if a business rule changes - a calculated margin defined wrong can be fixed only if revenue and cost were retained. This is why warehouses often store both the raw inputs and the derived metrics rather than overwriting one with the other.</p>"},
  {heading:"Merging, Appending, Imputation, and Deletion", body:"<p>This final Domain 2 section gathers the decision-level transformations: <span class='keyterm'>merging</span> and <span class='keyterm'>appending</span> combine datasets, while <span class='keyterm'>imputation</span> and <span class='keyterm'>deletion</span> are the two strategies for handling the missing values discovered during profiling. Choosing wisely among them is the capstone judgment the exam tests, because each choice trades data volume against data integrity.</p><h3>Merging versus appending - one more time</h3><p>It is worth cementing the distinction because tools blur it. <span class='keyterm'>Merging</span> (the pandas/Power Query term for a join) combines datasets <em>horizontally</em>, matching on a key to add columns - the same operation as a SQL JOIN. <span class='keyterm'>Appending</span> combines datasets <em>vertically</em>, stacking rows that share a structure - the same operation as SQL UNION/UNION ALL. Merging answers \"add more attributes to each record\"; appending answers \"add more records.\"</p><table><thead><tr><th></th><th>Merge (join)</th><th>Append (union)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Direction</td><td>Horizontal (adds columns)</td><td>Vertical (adds rows)</td></tr><tr><td>Needs</td><td>A common key</td><td>Compatible columns</td></tr><tr><td>SQL term</td><td>JOIN</td><td>UNION / UNION ALL</td></tr><tr><td>pandas term</td><td>merge()</td><td>concat()</td></tr><tr><td>Risk</td><td>Fan-out, unmatched rows</td><td>Misaligned columns, dups</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Imputation: filling missing values</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Imputation</span> replaces missing values with estimated ones so you can keep the records. The common strategies:</p><ul><li><span class='keyterm'>Mean / median / mode imputation</span> - fill with the column's average (mean), middle value (median, better when skewed or with outliers), or most frequent value (mode, for categories).</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Forward / backward fill</span> - carry the previous (or next) value forward, common in time series where the last known reading is a reasonable estimate.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Constant / flag imputation</span> - fill with a placeholder like \"Unknown\" and optionally add a flag column marking that the value was imputed.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Model-based imputation</span> - predict the missing value from other columns (regression, k-nearest neighbors) for higher accuracy at higher cost.</li></ul><pre># pandas imputation\ndf['age'] = df['age'].fillna(df['age'].median())          # median\ndf['region'] = df['region'].fillna(df['region'].mode()[0]) # mode\ndf['reading'] = df['reading'].ffill()                      # forward fill</pre><h3>Deletion: removing incomplete data</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Deletion</span> simply removes data with missing values. <span class='keyterm'>Listwise deletion</span> (complete-case analysis) drops any row with <em>any</em> missing value; <span class='keyterm'>pairwise deletion</span> uses available data per calculation, excluding a row only from analyses involving its missing field. You may also drop an entire <em>column</em> that is mostly empty. Deletion is simple and avoids introducing fabricated values, but it shrinks the dataset and - critically - can <em>bias</em> results if the missingness is not random (MNAR), because the dropped rows differ systematically from those that remain.</p><h3>Choosing imputation versus deletion</h3><table><thead><tr><th>Situation</th><th>Prefer</th><th>Why</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Tiny % missing, random (MCAR)</td><td>Deletion</td><td>Negligible data loss, no fabrication</td></tr><tr><td>Large % missing, valuable rows</td><td>Imputation</td><td>Deleting would gut the dataset</td></tr><tr><td>Column mostly empty</td><td>Drop the column</td><td>Too sparse to be reliable</td></tr><tr><td>Missingness depends on the value (MNAR)</td><td>Neither blindly</td><td>Both bias results; investigate first</td></tr><tr><td>Time series gap</td><td>Forward/backward fill</td><td>Last known value is a fair estimate</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p><strong>Merge</strong> = join = add columns by key; <strong>append</strong> = union = add rows. For missing data, <strong>imputation</strong> fills estimates (use <em>median</em> over mean when outliers are present, <em>mode</em> for categories) to keep records; <strong>deletion</strong> drops them. Delete when the missing share is tiny and random; impute when rows are too valuable to lose. Both can bias results when data is MNAR - so diagnose the cause first.</p></div><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>A 50,000-row customer table has 2 percent of ages missing at random and 60 percent of \"secondary phone\" missing. The analyst imputes the few missing ages with the median (preserving nearly all rows), drops the secondary-phone column entirely (too sparse to trust), and discovers that missing <em>income</em> values cluster among high-net-worth clients who declined to disclose - an MNAR pattern - so rather than mean-fill and understate income, she flags those rows and analyzes them separately.</p></div><h3>The hidden risk of mean imputation</h3><p>Mean imputation is the most common method and also the most quietly damaging when overused, so the exam expects you to know its side effects. Filling many missing values with the column mean artificially <em>shrinks the variance</em> of that column - the imputed values all sit exactly at the average, so the spread of the data narrows and the standard deviation falls. This distorts any later analysis that depends on dispersion, and it weakens correlations between the imputed column and others, because the substituted constant carries no relationship to the other variables. Median imputation suffers less distortion on skewed data, and model-based methods (predicting the missing value from correlated columns) preserve relationships far better at the cost of complexity. The lesson is that imputation is never free: it lets you keep rows, but it injects fabricated values whose effect on variance and correlation must be understood, not ignored.</p><h3>Matching the technique to the missingness mechanism</h3><p>The choice among these techniques should follow the missingness diagnosis from earlier in the domain. When data is missing completely at random (MCAR) and the share is small, listwise deletion is safe because the dropped rows are a random subset that does not bias the remainder. When data is missing at random (MAR) - missingness predictable from other observed variables - model-based imputation that uses those variables is the principled choice. When data is missing not at random (MNAR) - missingness tied to the hidden value itself, like high earners declining to report income - both naive deletion and mean imputation introduce systematic bias, and the honest response is to flag and analyze those records separately, or to gather more data, rather than to paper over the gap. This is the through-line of Domain 2: you profile first to learn <em>why</em> data is missing, then choose a handling technique whose assumptions match that cause.</p><h3>Document every decision</h3><p>Whatever you choose, record it. Imputation fabricates values, so downstream consumers must know which figures are real and which are estimated; an <em>imputation flag</em> column makes this explicit. Deletion changes row counts, so reconciliations must account for it. The professional standard is a documented, reproducible cleansing pipeline in which every merge, append, imputation, and deletion is logged - so a result can be audited, defended, and rerun. This closes the loop on Domain 2: data acquired thoughtfully, profiled honestly, and transformed transparently is data an analyst can stake a decision on.</p>"}
);
